ily School, Dansville, Livingston County\n*All Saints Catholic Academy, Gates\n*Catherine McAuley, Greece\n*Corpus Christi, Rochester\n*Good Shepherd, Henrietta\n*Holy Cross, Rochester (reopened in 2011)\n*Holy Family, Rochester\n*Holy Trinity, Webster\n*St. Andrews, Rochester\n*St. Boniface, Rochester\n*St. John of Rochester, Fairport\n*St. John the Evangelist, Spencerport\n*St. Margaret Mary, Irondequoit\n*St. Monica, Rochester\n\n===High schools===\nThere remain five traditionally Catholic high schools (or combined junior/senior high schools) in the diocese.  These schools were founded by various [[Religious institute (Catholic)|Roman Catholic religious orders]] and operate independently of the diocese itself.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Schools'''\n|-\n! School !! Founding Religious Order !! Location !! Established !! Grades\n|-\n| [[Aquinas Institute]] || [[Congregation of St. Basil|Basilian]] || [[Rochester, New York|Rochester, Monroe County]] || 1902 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Bishop Kearney High School (Irondequoit, New York)|Bishop Kearney High School]] || [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]], [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|Sisters of Notre Dame]] || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || 1962 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[McQuaid Jesuit High School]] || [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1954 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Notre Dame High School (Elmira, New York)|Notre Dame High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Elmira, New York|Elmira, Chemung County]] || 1955 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[Our Lady of Mercy High School (New York)|Our Lady of Mercy High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1928 || Grades 6 through 12\n|}\n<gallery>\nFile:Aquinas Institute front entrance.JPG|Aquinas Institute\nFile:Bishop Kearney High School.JPG|Bishop Kearney High School\nFile:McQuaidJesuitHighSchoolFrontEntranceB.JPG|McQuaid Jesuit High School\nFile:GreeceOdysseyAcademyFrontEntrance.JPG|The former Cardinal Mooney High School\n</gallery>\n\n====Former high schools====\n*Academy of the Sacred Heart, Rochester, Monroe County, 1855\u20131969\n*[[Cardinal Mooney High School (Greece, New York)|Cardinal Mooney High School]], Greece, Monroe County, 1962\u20131989\n*[[DeSales High School (Geneva, New York)|DeSales High School]], Geneva, Ontario County, 1912\u20132012\n*[[Nazareth Academy (Rochester, New York)|Nazareth Academy]], Rochester, Monroe County, 1871\u20132010\n*St. Agnes High School, Rochester, Monroe County, 1954\u20131982\n*King's Preparatory, Rochester, Monroe County, 1967-1970\n*St. Anthony of Padua College Prep School, Watkins Glen, Schuyler County, 1949-1970\n\n===Former seminaries===\n*St. Andrew's Preparatory Seminary, 1870\u20131967\n*[[Saint Bernard's Seminary]], 1893\u20131981\n\n===Former liberal arts colleges===\n*[[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College for Women]], became independent in the 1970s\n*[[St. John Fisher College|St. John Fisher College for Men]], became independent in 1968\n\n==Former charitable institutions==\n*St. Ann's Home (now St. Ann's Community)\n*St. Joseph's Orphan Asylum (later St. Joseph's Villa, now Villa of Hope)<ref>{{cite web | url = https://villaofhope.org/About-Us/History | title = Villa of Hope History | year = 2020 | work = Organization website | publisher = Villa of Hope | location = [[Rochester, New York]] | accessdate = 2020-02-28}}</ref>\n*St. Mary's Boys' Home\n*St. Mary's Hospital, Rochester, Monroe County\n*St. Patrick's Girls' Home\n\n==Counties==\nThis is a list of the counties in [[New York State]] that fall into the Diocese of Rochester:\n* [[Monroe County, New York|Monroe]]\n* [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]]\n* [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]]\n* [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]]\n* [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]]\n* [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]]\n* [[Yates County, New York|Yates]]\n* [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]]\n* [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] (added in 1896)\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image             = CoA_Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Rochester.svg\n|bannerimage       =\n|badgeimage        =\n|notes             = Arms was designed and adopted when the diocese was erected. It was designed in the 1930s by Pierre LaRose\n|year_adopted      = 1868\n|crest             =\n|torse             =\n|helm              =\n|escutcheon        =  The arms of the diocese are composed of a [[saltire]] with a crescent in the center.\n|supporters        =\n|compartment       =\n|motto             = \n|orders            =\n|other_elements    =\n|banner            =\n|badge             =\n|symbolism         =  The St. Andrew's Cross (saltire) was taken from the coat of arms of the original [[Diocese of Rochester]] in England (now an Anglican diocese). The new design is distinguished from the original, by changing a scallop shell in the center to the crescent symbol of the Immaculate Conception. The cross emphasizes the bishop as the successor to the apostles, and the bishop's charge to preach and live the Word of God faithfully and to witness to the Resurrection. \n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dor.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester Official Site]\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Diocese of Rochester}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of New York}}\n{{coord|43|09|56|N|77|36|41|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester|*]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2019]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Rochester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Rochester\n| latin             = Dioecesis Roffensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = SacredHeartCathedralRochesterNewYorkWestView.JPG\n| image_size        = 250px\n| caption           = Sacred Heart Cathedral\n| coat              = CoA Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester.svg\n| coat_size         = 150px\n| image_alt         = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = United States\n| metropolitan      = [[Timothy M. Dolan]]\n| territory         = [[Monroe County, New York|Counties of Monroe]], [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]], [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]], [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]], [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]], [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]], [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]], [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]], [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]], [[Yates County, New York|Yates]], [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] and [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of New York]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 8,772 \n| population        = 1,570,000\n| population_as_of  = 2014\n| catholics         = 350,000<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 23\n| parishes          = <!-- Number of parishes in the diocese --> 106\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese --> 172\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese --> 172\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese --> 27 \n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = March 3, 1868\n| cathedral         = [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Rochester)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[St. John Fisher]] \n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese --> 251\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]]\n| apostolic_admin   = \n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = Very Rev. Paul J. Tomasso\n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Matthew H. Clark]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Rochester map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = {{URL|http://www.dor.org}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester''' is a [[diocese]] of the [[Catholicism|Catholic Church]] in the Greater [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]] region of [[New York State]] in the [[United States]]. The region that the Diocese comprises extends from its northern border on the south shore of [[Lake Ontario]] through the [[Finger Lakes]] region to its southern border at the [[New York (state)|New York]]-[[Pennsylvania]] border. \n\nThe Diocese of Rochester comprises 12 counties in New York, with approximately 350,000 Catholics and over 125 faith communities (parishes and chapels), 22 diocesan elementary schools and 7 independent parochial high schools. The bishop of the diocese is currently [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]]. The metropolitan for the diocese is the Archbishop of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of New York]], currently Cardinal [[Timothy Dolan]]. The [[cathedral]] [[parish]] for the diocese is [[Sacred Heart Cathedral (Rochester)|Sacred Heart Cathedral]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:St. Patrick's Cathedral - Rochester, New York.jpg|thumb|left|St. Patrick's Cathedral in Rochester (1868-1937)]]\nThe Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester began on March 3, 1868, when [[Pope Pius IX]] entrusted eight counties (Monroe, Livingston, Wayne, Ontario, Seneca, Cayuga, Yates, and Tompkins) within the Diocese of Buffalo to [[Bernard J. McQuaid]], the first bishop of Rochester. The new diocese had about 54,500 Catholics in 35 parish churches and 29 mission churches.\n\nIn 1896, the counties of Schuyler, Tioga, Chemung, and Steuben were added to the Diocese of Rochester from the Diocese of Buffalo, forming the current boundaries.\n\nThe diocese grew as Catholic immigrants came to western New York, peaking in the 1960s. Since then, the Catholic population has stabilized while the numbers of ordained presbyters (priests) and women religious (sisters) has fallen.<ref>[http://www.dor.org/dorhomepage/history.htm Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester - Diocesan History]</ref>\n*In 1909, there were 121,000 Catholics in 93 parishes, 36 missions and 53 parish schools with 18,000 pupils. There were 164 priests and more than 500 sisters.\n*In 1938, there were 223,657 Catholics in 129 parishes, 36 missions and 72 parish schools serving 23,796 pupils. There were 289 active diocesan priests.\n*In 1966, there were 361,790 Catholics in 155 parishes, 36 mission churches and 99 elementary parish schools serving 45,540 pupils. There were 371 active diocesan priests and 1,549 sisters.\n*In 1978, there were 358,850 Catholics in 161 parishes, 29 mission churches and 75 schools serving 19,526 pupils. There were 311 active diocesan priests and 1,095 women religious.\n*In 1992, there were 361,384 Catholics in 162 parishes and 58 elementary schools serving 11,992 pupils. There were 208 active diocesan priests and 842 sisters.\n\nOn September 22nd 2017 the Diocese of Rochester inaugurated its sesquicentennial anniversary marked by a solemn mass at Sacred Heart Cathedral. This event marks a year long celebration celebrating one hundred and fifty years and the year of the Eucharist which was proclaimed by Bishop Salvatore Matano on the Feast of Corpus Christi.\n\n==Reports of sex abuse and bankruptcy==\n\nIn June 2018, it was revealed that the Diocese had secretly paid $1.6 million since 1950 in compensation to 20 sex abuse victims.<ref>https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/local/columnists/andreatta/2018/06/09/andreatta-diocese-rochester-has-paid-1-6-m-20-sex-abuse-victims/686390002/</ref> Most of the payments occurred after the eruption of the 2002 clergy sex abuse scandal, although some are decades old. On June 10, 2019, a man claiming that he had been molested between 1969 and 1971 by local priest Rev. Francis Vogt filed a lawsuit against the Diocese of Rochester and several other local Catholic organizations affiliated the Diocese, claiming that they shielded Vogt from potential prosecution.<ref name=grownnot>https://13wham.com/news/local/victim-sues-diocese-of-rochester-over-claims-of-sexual-abuse-by-priest</ref> On September 12, 2019, the Diocese filed for [[Chapter 11 Bankruptcy]] in the wake of lawsuits against priests and other ministers who served in the Diocese.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.democratandchronicle.com/story/news/2019/09/12/rochester-ny-catholic-diocese-bankruptcy-sex-abuse-lawsuits-child-victims-act-cva-chapter-11/2297878001/|title=Diocese bankruptcy: Matano says it was 'a very difficult and painful decision'|last=Orr|first=Steve|date=September 12, 2019|work=Rochester Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref> <ref name=protectionnotgood /> The Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester is the first Catholic diocese in the state of New York to file for bankruptcy and also the 20th Catholic diocese in the U.S. to do so.<ref name=protectionnotgood>https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2019/09/12/catholic-sex-abuse-rochester-diocese-files-bankruptcy-protection/2308133001/</ref>\n\n==Bishops==\nThe following are lists of bishops and their years of service:\n\n===Bishops of Rochester===\n# [[Bernard J. McQuaid]] (1868-1909)\n# [[Thomas Francis Hickey (bishop)|Thomas F. Hickey]] (1909-1928), appointed [[Archbishop]] (ad personam) upon retirement\n# [[John Francis O'Hern]] (1929-1933)\n# [[Edward Aloysius Mooney|Edward A. Mooney]] (1933-1937), Archbishop (ad personam), appointed [[Archdiocese of Detroit|Archbishop of Detroit]] ([[Cardinal (Catholic Church)|Cardinal]] in 1946)\n# [[James E. Kearney]] (1937-1966)\n# Venerable [[Fulton J. Sheen]] (1966-1969), appointed [[Archbishop]] (ad personam) upon retirement\n# [[Joseph Lloyd Hogan]] (1969-1978) \n# [[Matthew H. Clark]] (1979-2012) \n# [[Salvatore Ronald Matano]] (2014-present)\n\n===Coadjutor Bishop===\n* [[Thomas Francis Hickey (bishop)|Thomas F. Hickey]] (1905-1909)\n\n===Auxiliary Bishops===\n* [[Lawrence B. Casey]] (1953-1966), appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Paterson|Bishop of Paterson]]\n* [[John Edgar McCafferty]] (1968-1980)\n* [[Dennis Walter Hickey]] (1968-1990)\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n*[[Edward Joseph Hanna]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco|Auxiliary Bishop of San Francisco]] in 1912 and later [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of San Francisco|Archbishop of San Francisco]]\n*[[Walter Andrew Foery]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse]] in 1937\n*[[James Michael Moynihan]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Syracuse|Bishop of Syracuse]] in 1995\n\n==Schools==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ '''Superintendents of the Monroe County Catholic School System'''\n|-\n! Name !! Tenure\n|-\n|  Sr. Roberta Tierney, [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|SSND]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = Sr. Roberta Tierney; directed education - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/obituaries/sr-roberta-tierney-directed-education/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n||  1976 \u2013 1978 \n|-\n|Timothy Leahy\n|1978 - 1979\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/in-depth/back-to-school/previous-stories/siena-principal-taught-responsibility/?keywords=Timothy%20Leahy&tag=&searchSectionID=\n|Rev. Richard C. Kinsky, CSB\n|1979 - 1981\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/news/obituaries/father-richard-c-kinsky-csb-76/\n|Sr. Edwardine Weaver, RSM\n|1981 - 1986\n|-http://catholiccourier.com/in-depth/milestonesvocations/milestones-vocations-2013/sisters-of-mercy-mark-a-total-of-955-years-of-service/?keywords=Edwardine%20Weaver,%20RSM&tag=&searchSectionID=\n|Br. Brian Walsh, [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|CFC]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = New schools head brings fresh ideas - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/local-news/new-schools-head-brings-fresh-ideas/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref>\n|July 1986 \u2013 1 July 1991\n|-\n|Sr. Mary Ann Binsack, [[Religious Sisters of Mercy|RSM]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url = http://lib.catholiccourier.com/1992-catholic-courier/catholic-courier-1992%20-%200447.pdf|title = Schools superintendent to stress long view|last = Cullivan|first = Rob|date = May 28, 1992|work = Catholic Courier|access-date = November 25, 2015|via = }}</ref>\n|1991 \u2013 1992\n|-\n| Timothy W. Dwyer<ref name=\":0\" /> || 1992 \u2013 2001\n|-\n| Sr. Elizabeth Meegan, [[Dominican Order|OP]]<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = New schools head brings fresh ideas - Catholic Courier|url = http://www.catholiccourier.com/news/local-news/new-schools-head-brings-fresh-ideas/|website = www.catholiccourier.com|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> || 2001 \u2013 2006\n|-\n| Sr. Elaine Poitras, CSC<ref name=\":1\" /> || 2006 \u2013 January 2008\n|-\n| Sr. Janice Morgan, [[Sisters of St. Joseph|CSJ]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = DOR Catholic: Update on Sister Janice Morgan|url = http://dorcatholic.blogspot.com/2009/02/update-on-sister-janice-morgan.html|website = DOR Catholic|date = 2009-02-27|accessdate = 2015-11-25}}</ref> || January 2008 \u2013 August 2008\n|-\n| Anne Willkens Leach || August 2008 \u2013 July 2013\n|-\n| Anthony S. Cook III<ref>http://www.dor.org/index.cfm/news/news-docs/new-schools-superintendent-named/</ref> || 1 July 2013 \u2013 present\n|}\n\n===Primary schools===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Schools'''<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.dorschools.org/discover-our-schools | title = Discover Our Schools | year = 2012 | work = Catholic Schools Diocese of Rochester | publisher = Diocese of Rochester | location = [[Rochester, New York]] | accessdate = 2013-01-02}}</ref>\n|-\n! School !! Parish !! Location !! Established !! Grades\n|-\n| All Saints Academy || St. Mary || [[Corning (city), New York|Corning, Steuben County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 8\n|-\n| Holy Cross School || Holy Cross || [[Charlotte, Rochester, New York|Rochester, Monroe County]] || 2011 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| Holy Family Primary School || St. Mary || [[Elmira, New York|Elmira, Chemung County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Agnes School || St. Agnes || [[Avon (village), New York|Avon, Livingston County]] || 1878 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Francis de Sales - St. Stephen School || Our Lady of Peace || [[Geneva, New York|Geneva, Ontario County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 8\n|-\n| St. John Neumann School || St. John the Evangelist || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Joseph Elementary School || St. Joseph || [[Auburn, New York|Auburn, Cayuga County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 5\n|-\n| St. Joseph School || St. Joseph || [[Penfield, New York|Penfield, Monroe County]] || 1960 || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Kateri School || Christ the King || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Lawrence School || St. Lawrence || [[Greece (town), New York|Greece, Monroe County]] || || Pre-K through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Louis School || St. Louis || [[Pittsford, New York|Pittsford, Monroe County]] || || Pre-School through Grade 6\n|-\n| St. Mary S