bishop-accountability.org/news2008/01_02/2008_01_19_Bryant_AsBishop.htm | archivedate = 2008}}</ref>\n*Holy Family School, Dansville, Livingston County\n*All Saints Catholic Academy, Gates\n*Catherine McAuley, Greece\n*Corpus Christi, Rochester\n*Good Shepherd, Henrietta\n*Holy Cross, Rochester (reopened in 2011)\n*Holy Family, Rochester\n*Holy Trinity, Webster\n*St. Andrews, Rochester\n*St. Boniface, Rochester\n*St. John of Rochester, Fairport\n*St. John the Evangelist, Spencerport\n*St. Margaret Mary, Irondequoit\n*St. Monica, Rochester\n\n===High schools===\nThere remain five traditionally Catholic high schools (or combined junior/senior high schools) in the diocese.  These schools were founded by various [[Religious institute (Catholic)|Roman Catholic religious orders]] and operate independently of the diocese itself.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ '''Schools'''\n|-\n! School !! Founding Religious Order !! Location !! Established !! Grades\n|-\n| [[Aquinas Institute]] || [[Congregation of St. Basil|Basilian]] || [[Rochester, New York|Rochester, Monroe County]] || 1902 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Bishop Kearney High School (Irondequoit, New York)|Bishop Kearney High School]] || [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Christian Brothers]], [[School Sisters of Notre Dame|Sisters of Notre Dame]] || [[Irondequoit, New York|Irondequoit, Monroe County]] || 1962 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[McQuaid Jesuit High School]] || [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1954 || Grades 6 through 12\n|-\n| [[Notre Dame High School (Elmira, New York)|Notre Dame High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Elmira, New York|Elmira, Chemung County]] || 1955 || Grades 7 through 12\n|-\n| [[Our Lady of Mercy High School (New York)|Our Lady of Mercy High School]] || [[Sisters of Mercy]] || [[Brighton, Monroe County, New York|Brighton, Monroe County]] || 1928 || Grades 6 through 12\n|}\n<gallery>\nFile:Aquinas Institute front entrance.JPG|Aquinas Institute\nFile:Bishop Kearney High School.JPG|Bishop Kearney High School\nFile:McQuaidJesuitHighSchoolFrontEntranceB.JPG|McQuaid Jesuit High School\nFile:GreeceOdysseyAcademyFrontEntrance.JPG|The former Cardinal Mooney High School\n</gallery>\n\n====Former high schools====\n*Academy of the Sacred Heart, Rochester, Monroe County, 1855\u20131969\n*[[Cardinal Mooney High School (Greece, New York)|Cardinal Mooney High School]], Greece, Monroe County, 1962\u20131989\n*[[DeSales High School (Geneva, New York)|DeSales High School]], Geneva, Ontario County, 1912\u20132012\n*[[Nazareth Academy (Rochester, New York)|Nazareth Academy]], Rochester, Monroe County, 1871\u20132010\n*St. Agnes High School, Rochester, Monroe County, 1954\u20131982\n*King's Preparatory, Rochester, Monroe County, 1967-1970\n*St. Anthony of Padua College Prep School, Watkins Glen, Schuyler County, 1949-1970\n\n===Former seminaries===\n*St. Andrew's Preparatory Seminary, 1870\u20131967\n*[[Saint Bernard's Seminary]], 1893\u20131981\n\n===Former liberal arts colleges===\n*[[Nazareth College (New York)|Nazareth College for Women]], became independent in the 1970s\n*[[St. John Fisher College|St. John Fisher College for Men]], became independent in 1968\n\n==Former charitable institutions==\n*St. Ann's Home (now St. Ann's Community)\n*St. Joseph's Orphan Asylum (later St. Joseph's Villa, now Villa of Hope)<ref>{{cite web | url = https://villaofhope.org/About-Us/History | title = Villa of Hope History | year = 2020 | work = Organization website | publisher = Villa of Hope | location = [[Rochester, New York]] | accessdate = 2020-02-28}}</ref>\n*St. Mary's Boys' Home\n*St. Mary's Hospital, Rochester, Monroe County\n*St. Patrick's Girls' Home\n\n==Counties==\nThis is a list of the counties in [[New York State]] that fall into the Diocese of Rochester:\n* [[Monroe County, New York|Monroe]]\n* [[Livingston County, New York|Livingston]]\n* [[Wayne County, New York|Wayne]]\n* [[Ontario County, New York|Ontario]]\n* [[Seneca County, New York|Seneca]]\n* [[Cayuga County, New York|Cayuga]]\n* [[Yates County, New York|Yates]]\n* [[Tompkins County, New York|Tompkins]]\n* [[Schuyler County, New York|Schuyler]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Tioga County, New York|Tioga]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Chemung County, New York|Chemung]] (added in 1896)\n* [[Steuben County, New York|Steuben]] (added in 1896)\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image             = CoA_Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Rochester.svg\n|bannerimage       =\n|badgeimage        =\n|notes             = Arms was designed and adopted when the diocese was erected. It was designed in the 1930s by Pierre LaRose\n|year_adopted      = 1868\n|crest             =\n|torse             =\n|helm              =\n|escutcheon        =  The arms of the diocese are composed of a [[saltire]] with a crescent in the center.\n|supporters        =\n|compartment       =\n|motto             = \n|orders            =\n|other_elements    =\n|banner            =\n|badge             =\n|symbolism         =  The St. Andrew's Cross (saltire) was taken from the coat of arms of the original [[Diocese of Rochester]] in England (now an Anglican diocese). The new design is distinguished from the original, by changing a scallop shell in the center to the crescent symbol of the Immaculate Conception. The cross emphasizes the bishop as the successor to the apostles, and the bishop's charge to preach and live the Word of God faithfully and to witness to the Resurrection. \n|previous_versions =\n}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dor.org/ Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester Official Site]\n*{{CathEncy|wstitle=Diocese of Rochester}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of New York}}\n{{coord|43|09|56|N|77|36|41|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1868]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester|*]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century]]\n[[Category:1868 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Companies that filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 2019]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Rochester]]\n", "name_user": "Freddiem", "label": "safe", "comment": "simplify link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Rochester"}
{"title_page": "David Deming (economist)", "text_new": "{{about|the Harvard Graduate School of Education economist|the University of Oklahoma geologist|David Deming}}\n{{Infobox economist\n| name             = David J. Deming\n| school_tradition =\n| color            =\n| image            = \n| image_size       =\n| caption          =\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[United States|American]]\n| institution      = [[Harvard University]]\n| field            = [[education economics]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Ohio State University]]<br>[[University of California at Berkeley]]<br>[[Harvard University]]\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| contributions    = \n| awards           =\n| spouse           =\n| signature        = <!-- file name only -->\n| repec_prefix = e | repec_id = pde497\n}}\n'''David J. Deming''' is a [[United States|U.S. American]] [[economist]] and Professor of Public Policy at the [[Harvard Kennedy School]],<ref>[https://scholar.harvard.edu/ddeming/home Profile of David Deming on the website of Harvard University. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> Professor of Education and Economics at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] and Director of the Malcolm Wiener Center for Social Policy.<ref>[https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/david-deming Faculty profile of David Deming on the website of the Harvard Graduate School of Education. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref><ref>[https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2019/4/25/david-deming-wiener-center/ Chaidez, A.A. (April 25th, 2019). David Deming Named Faculty Director of Harvard Kennedy School Wiener Center. In: ''The Crimson''. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> His research focuses on the [[education economics|economics of education]] in general and the impact of [[education policy|education policies]] on long-run non-test score outcomes. In 2018, David Deming received the David N. Kershaw Award and Prize from the [[Association for Public Policy Analysis and Management]] for his work in the areas of [[secondary education]], [[vocational training]] and [[skill]]s.<ref>[https://opportunityinsights.org/updates/david-deming-named-winner-of-2018-david-n-kershaw-award-and-prize/ Opportunity Insights (November 7th, 2018). David Deming Named Winner of 2018 David N. Kershaw Award and Prize. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref>\n\n== Biography==\n\nDavid Deming earned a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in [[economics]] and a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[political science]] from [[Ohio State University]] in 2002, followed by a [[Master of Public Policy|M.P.P.]] from [[University of California at Berkeley|UC Berkeley]]'s [[Goldman School of Public Policy]] in 2005 and a [[Ph.D.]] in Public Policy from the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]] (HKS) in 2010. After his Ph.D., Deming joined [[Carnegie Mellon University]] as [[assistant professor]] of public policy and economics before moving to the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] (HGSE) as assistant and later as [[associate professor]]. Since 2016, Deming has been a full professor of both HGSE and HKS. Moreover, he became director of the Malcolm Wiener Center for Social Policy at HKS in 2019.<ref>[https://scholar.harvard.edu/files/ddeming/files/demingcv.pdf Curriculum vitae of David Deming on the website of Harvard University. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> He is affiliated with the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], [[ifo Institute for Economic Research|CESifo]], and [[Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab|J-PAL]],<ref>[https://www.povertyactionlab.org/deming Profile of David Deming on the website of J-PAL. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> and is a Principal Investigator of the [http://climbinitiative.org CLIMB Initiative],<ref>[http://climbinitiative.org/team/ Profile of CLIMB Initiative's team. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> which seeks to use [[big data|big data analysis]] to identify higher education policies and programmes in support of students. He is a great person. He is also very nice and educated.\n\n== Research==\n\nDavid Deming's research interests centres on the [[education economics|economics of education]], with a focus on [[early childhood education|early childhood]], [[primary education|primary]] and [[secondary education]] as well as the long-term non-test score outcomes of education policies.<ref>[https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/david-deming Faculty profile of David Deming on the website of Harvard Graduate School of Education. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> Key findings of his research include:\n\nConcerning early childhood education, Deming has studied the impact of [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]], finding that participants gain 0.23 [[standard deviation|SD]] on a summary index of young adult outcomes, which closes one-third of the gap between children from the median and bottom quartile family income.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/app.1.3.111 Deming, D. (2009). Early childhood intervention and life-cycle skill development: Evidence from Head Start. ''American Economic Journal: Applied Economics'', 1(3), pp. 111-134.]</ref> In earlier research with [[Susan Dynarski]], he has also highlighted criticized [[Redshirting (academic)|redshirting]], i.e., the continuously increasing practice of postponing the entry of children into school, arguing that little evidence supports the notion that doing so benefits children and some evidence suggests that redshirting reduces educational attainment by increasing high school dropout rates and depresses lifetime earnings by delaying entry into the labour market.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/jep.22.3.71 Deming, D., Dynarski, S. (2008). The lengthening of childhood. ''Journal of Economic Perspectives'', 22(3), pp. 71-92.]</ref>\n\nIn research with Dynarski on the link between college costs and educational attainment, he highlights the potential of college costs to depress college entry and persistence, arguing that simple and transparent programmes in general and programmes linking money to incentives and/or the takeup of academic support services in particular appear to be most effective.<ref>[https://scholar.harvard.edu/files/ddeming/files/deming_dynarski_robinhood.pdf Deming, D., Dynarski, S. (2009). Into college, out of poverty? Policies to increase the postsecondary attainment of the poor. ''NBER Working Paper Series'', No. 15387.]</ref>\n\nDeming estimated that, in [[North Carolina]],  giving students and their families the choice which secondary school they attend substantially helped to reduce crime and incarceration rates among those given the choice, with the impacts being concentrated among high-risk youth whose propensity to become criminal and to commit severe crimes is cut by about half.<ref>[https://academic.oup.com/qje/article-abstract/126/4/2063/1922935?redirectedFrom=fulltext Deming, D.J. (2011). Better Schools, Less Crime? ''Quarterly Journal of Economics'', 126(4), pp. 2063-2115.]</ref> In further work with [[Thomas Kane (economist)|Thomas Kane]], [[Douglas Staiger]] and Judith Hastings, Deming finds that giving such the choice of school to students and their families induces them to generally choose public schools that are generally of higher quality, which in turn tends to raise girls' college attainment as these are most likely to benefit from improved learning environments.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/42920726 Deming, D.J. et al. (2014). School Choice, School Quality and Postsecondary Attainment. ''American Economic Review'', 104(3), pp. 991-1013.]</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Claudia Goldin]] and [[Lawrence F. Katz]], Deming has  investigated the for-profit sector of U.S. higher education , observing that for-profit students are comparatively more likely to be unemployed or \"idle\" and to earn less after graduation as well as to have far higher default rates on their student loans relative to comparable students from non-profit institutions; by contrast, for-profits tend to educate a larger fraction of minority, disadvantaged and older student and are more successful in first-year student retention and AA and certificate level completion.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/jep.26.1.139 Deming, D., Goldin, C., Katz, L. (2012). The for-profit postsecondary school sector: nimble critters or agile predators? ''Journal of Economic Perspectives'', 26(1), pp. 139-164.]</ref> In further research with them as well as with Noam Yuchtman and Amira Abulafi, Deming finds that a business bachelor's degree from a for-profit online institution is 22% less likely to receive a callback from an employer than one from a nonselective public institution, especially in the absence of external quality indicators.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.20141757 Deming, D.J. et al. (2016). The value of postsecondary credentials in the labor market: An experimental study. ''American Economic Review'', 106(3), pp. 778-806.]</ref> Examining whether online learning technologies have helped decrease prices in higher education, they find that real and relative prices for full-time undergraduate online education has fallen between 2006 and 2013, raising hopes that edtech can \"bend the cost curve\" of U.S. higher education, although they caution that the impact of online learning on education quality remains uncertain.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.p20151024 Deming, D.J. et al. (2015). Can Online Learning Bend the Higher Education Cost Curve? ''American Economic Review'', 105(5), pp. 496-501.]</ref>\n\nRelative to the 1980s and 1990s, the U.S. labour market increasingly rewarded social skills in the 2010s, especially in combination with math skills, which Deming attributes to social skills reducing coordination costs and enabling worker specialization and cooperation.<ref>[https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/132/4/1593/3861633 Deming, D.J. (2017). The growing importance of social skills in the labor market. ''Quarterly Journal of Economics'', 132(4), pp. 1593-1640.]</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n\n*Deming has performed editorial duties for the ''[[Journal of Human Resources]]'', ''[[American Economic Journal: Economic Policy]]'' and the ''[[American Economic Journal: Applied Economics]]''.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/journals/app/about-app/editors Editors of the ''American Economic Journal: Applied Economics''. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> \n*In 2018, his research was awarded the David N. Kershaw Award and Prize by the [[Association for Public Policy Analysis and Management]].\n\n== References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/demingdavid/david-deming Homepage of David Deming]\n* [https://scholar.harvard.edu/ddeming/home Webpage of David Deming on the website of Harvard University]\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=F2pYbMcAAAAJ&hl=en Google Scholar page of David Deming]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deming, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Education economists]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education faculty]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:American economists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Harvard Graduate School of Education economist|the University of Oklahoma geologist|David Deming}}\n{{Infobox economist\n| name             = David J. Deming\n| school_tradition =\n| color            =\n| image            = \n| image_size       =\n| caption          =\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = \n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = [[United States|American]]\n| institution      = [[Harvard University]]\n| field            = [[education economics]]\n| alma_mater       = [[Ohio State University]]<br>[[University of California at Berkeley]]<br>[[Harvard University]]\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| contributions    = \n| awards           =\n| spouse           =\n| signature        = <!-- file name only -->\n| repec_prefix = e | repec_id = pde497\n}}\n'''David J. Deming''' is a [[United States|U.S. American]] [[economist]] and Professor of Public Policy at the [[Harvard Kennedy School]],<ref>[https://scholar.harvard.edu/ddeming/home Profile of David Deming on the website of Harvard University. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> Professor of Education and Economics at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] and Director of the Malcolm Wiener Center for Social Policy.<ref>[https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/david-deming Faculty profile of David Deming on the website of the Harvard Graduate School of Education. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref><ref>[https://www.thecrimson.com/article/2019/4/25/david-deming-wiener-center/ Chaidez, A.A. (April 25th, 2019). David Deming Named Faculty Director of Harvard Kennedy School Wiener Center. In: ''The Crimson''. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> His research focuses on the [[education economics|economics of education]] in general and the impact of [[education policy|education policies]] on long-run non-test score outcomes. In 2018, David Deming received the David N. Kershaw Award and Prize from the [[Association for Public Policy Analysis and Management]] for his work in the areas of [[secondary education]], [[vocational training]] and [[skill]]s.<ref>[https://opportunityinsights.org/updates/david-deming-named-winner-of-2018-david-n-kershaw-award-and-prize/ Opportunity Insights (November 7th, 2018). David Deming Named Winner of 2018 David N. Kershaw Award and Prize. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref>\n\n== Biography==\n\nDavid Deming earned a [[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]] in [[economics]] and a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[political science]] from [[Ohio State University]] in 2002, followed by a [[Master of Public Policy|M.P.P.]] from [[University of California at Berkeley|UC Berkeley]]'s [[Goldman School of Public Policy]] in 2005 and a [[Ph.D.]] in Public Policy from the [[John F. Kennedy School of Government|Harvard Kennedy School]] (HKS) in 2010. After his Ph.D., Deming joined [[Carnegie Mellon University]] as [[assistant professor]] of public policy and economics before moving to the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] (HGSE) as assistant and later as [[associate professor]]. Since 2016, Deming has been a full professor of both HGSE and HKS. Moreover, he became director of the Malcolm Wiener Center for Social Policy at HKS in 2019.<ref>[https://scholar.harvard.edu/files/ddeming/files/demingcv.pdf Curriculum vitae of David Deming on the website of Harvard University. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> He is affiliated with the [[National Bureau of Economic Research]], [[ifo Institute for Economic Research|CESifo]], and [[Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab|J-PAL]],<ref>[https://www.povertyactionlab.org/deming Profile of David Deming on the website of J-PAL. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> and is a Principal Investigator of the [http://climbinitiative.org CLIMB Initiative],<ref>[http://climbinitiative.org/team/ Profile of CLIMB Initiative's team. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> which seeks to use [[big data|big data analysis]] to identify higher education policies and programmes in support of students.\n\n== Research==\n\nDavid Deming's research interests centres on the [[education economics|economics of education]], with a focus on [[early childhood education|early childhood]], [[primary education|primary]] and [[secondary education]] as well as the long-term non-test score outcomes of education policies.<ref>[https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/david-deming Faculty profile of David Deming on the website of Harvard Graduate School of Education. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> Key findings of his research include:\n\nConcerning early childhood education, Deming has studied the impact of [[Head Start (program)|Head Start]], finding that participants gain 0.23 [[standard deviation|SD]] on a summary index of young adult outcomes, which closes one-third of the gap between children from the median and bottom quartile family income.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/app.1.3.111 Deming, D. (2009). Early childhood intervention and life-cycle skill development: Evidence from Head Start. ''American Economic Journal: Applied Economics'', 1(3), pp. 111-134.]</ref> In earlier research with [[Susan Dynarski]], he has also highlighted criticized [[Redshirting (academic)|redshirting]], i.e., the continuously increasing practice of postponing the entry of children into school, arguing that little evidence supports the notion that doing so benefits children and some evidence suggests that redshirting reduces educational attainment by increasing high school dropout rates and depresses lifetime earnings by delaying entry into the labour market.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/jep.22.3.71 Deming, D., Dynarski, S. (2008). The lengthening of childhood. ''Journal of Economic Perspectives'', 22(3), pp. 71-92.]</ref>\n\nIn research with Dynarski on the link between college costs and educational attainment, he highlights the potential of college costs to depress college entry and persistence, arguing that simple and transparent programmes in general and programmes linking money to incentives and/or the takeup of academic support services in particular appear to be most effective.<ref>[https://scholar.harvard.edu/files/ddeming/files/deming_dynarski_robinhood.pdf Deming, D., Dynarski, S. (2009). Into college, out of poverty? Policies to increase the postsecondary attainment of the poor. ''NBER Working Paper Series'', No. 15387.]</ref>\n\nDeming estimated that, in [[North Carolina]],  giving students and their families the choice which secondary school they attend substantially helped to reduce crime and incarceration rates among those given the choice, with the impacts being concentrated among high-risk youth whose propensity to become criminal and to commit severe crimes is cut by about half.<ref>[https://academic.oup.com/qje/article-abstract/126/4/2063/1922935?redirectedFrom=fulltext Deming, D.J. (2011). Better Schools, Less Crime? ''Quarterly Journal of Economics'', 126(4), pp. 2063-2115.]</ref> In further work with [[Thomas Kane (economist)|Thomas Kane]], [[Douglas Staiger]] and Judith Hastings, Deming finds that giving such the choice of school to students and their families induces them to generally choose public schools that are generally of higher quality, which in turn tends to raise girls' college attainment as these are most likely to benefit from improved learning environments.<ref>[https://www.jstor.org/stable/42920726 Deming, D.J. et al. (2014). School Choice, School Quality and Postsecondary Attainment. ''American Economic Review'', 104(3), pp. 991-1013.]</ref>\n\nTogether with [[Claudia Goldin]] and [[Lawrence F. Katz]], Deming has  investigated the for-profit sector of U.S. higher education , observing that for-profit students are comparatively more likely to be unemployed or \"idle\" and to earn less after graduation as well as to have far higher default rates on their student loans relative to comparable students from non-profit institutions; by contrast, for-profits tend to educate a larger fraction of minority, disadvantaged and older student and are more successful in first-year student retention and AA and certificate level completion.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/jep.26.1.139 Deming, D., Goldin, C., Katz, L. (2012). The for-profit postsecondary school sector: nimble critters or agile predators? ''Journal of Economic Perspectives'', 26(1), pp. 139-164.]</ref> In further research with them as well as with Noam Yuchtman and Amira Abulafi, Deming finds that a business bachelor's degree from a for-profit online institution is 22% less likely to receive a callback from an employer than one from a nonselective public institution, especially in the absence of external quality indicators.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.20141757 Deming, D.J. et al. (2016). The value of postsecondary credentials in the labor market: An experimental study. ''American Economic Review'', 106(3), pp. 778-806.]</ref> Examining whether online learning technologies have helped decrease prices in higher education, they find that real and relative prices for full-time undergraduate online education has fallen between 2006 and 2013, raising hopes that edtech can \"bend the cost curve\" of U.S. higher education, although they caution that the impact of online learning on education quality remains uncertain.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/aer.p20151024 Deming, D.J. et al. (2015). Can Online Learning Bend the Higher Education Cost Curve? ''American Economic Review'', 105(5), pp. 496-501.]</ref>\n\nRelative to the 1980s and 1990s, the U.S. labour market increasingly rewarded social skills in the 2010s, especially in combination with math skills, which Deming attributes to social skills reducing coordination costs and enabling worker specialization and cooperation.<ref>[https://academic.oup.com/qje/article/132/4/1593/3861633 Deming, D.J. (2017). The growing importance of social skills in the labor market. ''Quarterly Journal of Economics'', 132(4), pp. 1593-1640.]</ref>\n\n== Honors ==\n\n*Deming has performed editorial duties for the ''[[Journal of Human Resources]]'', ''[[American Economic Journal: Economic Policy]]'' and the ''[[American Economic Journal: Applied Economics]]''.<ref>[https://www.aeaweb.org/journals/app/about-app/editors Editors of the ''American Economic Journal: Applied Economics''. Retrieved July 22nd, 2019.]</ref> \n*In 2018, his research was awarded the David N. Kershaw Award and Prize by the [[Association for Public Policy Analysis and Management]].\n\n== References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links==\n\n* [https://sites.google.com/site/demingdavid/david-deming Homepage of David Deming]\n* [https://scholar.harvard.edu/ddeming/home Webpage of David Deming on the website of Harvard University]\n* [https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=F2pYbMcAAAAJ&hl=en Google Scholar page of David Deming]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Deming, David}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Education economists]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education faculty]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government faculty]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley alumni]]\n[[Category:American economists]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "209.6.130.217", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBiography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Deming_(economist)"}
{"title_page": "Kitchener, Ontario", "text_new": "{{Use Canadian English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name              = Kitchener\n|settlement_type   = [[List of cities in Ontario|City]] ([[List of municipalities in Ontario#Lower-tier municipalities|lower-tier]])\n|official_name     = City of Kitchener\n|image_skyline     = Arial photo of downtown Kitchener Ontario.JPG\n|image_caption     = View of Downtown Kitchener\n|motto             = ''Ex industria prosperitas'' ({{lang-la|Prosperity through industry}})\n|image_flag        =Flag of Kitchener, Ontario.svg\n|image_blank_emblem= Logo of Kitchener, Ontario.svg\n|blank_emblem_size = 100x90px\n|image_map         = Kitchener, Ontario.png\n|mapsize           = 200px\n|map_caption       = Location of Kitchener in Waterloo Region\n|pushpin_map = Canada Southern Ontario\n|pushpin_map_caption = Location of Kitchener in southern Ontario\n|subdivision_type  = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_type1 = [[Provinces and territories of Canada|Province]]\n|subdivision_name  = [[Canada]]\n|subdivision_name1 = [[Ontario]]\n|subdivision_type2 = [[Census divisions of Ontario|Region]]\n|subdivision_name2 = [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo|Waterloo]]\n|leader_title      = Mayor\n|leader_name = [[Berry Vrbanovic]]\n|leader_title2      = Governing Body\n|leader_name2 = [[Kitchener City Council]]\n|established_title = Founded\n|established_date  = 1833\n|established_title1= Incorporated\n|established_date1 = 1853\n|established_title2= Incorporated\n|established_date2 = 1912 (city)\n|area_footnotes    = <ref name=SC06/><ref name=SC06-ca/><ref>{{cite web |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0419&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&SearchText=Kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=0419&TABID=1&type=0 |website=Statistics Canada |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude    = 1 E8\n|area_total_km2    = 136.89\n|area_land_km2     = 136.89\n|area_water_km2    =\n|area_urban_km2    = 269.23\n|area_metro_km2    = 1,091.16\n|population_as_of  = 2016\n|population_footnotes = <ref name=SC06>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530013&Geo2=CD&Code2=3530&Data=Count&SearchText=kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Kitchener (city) census profile |publisher=[[Statistics Canada]] |work=[[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census data]] |accessdate=12 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213090426/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=3530013&Geo2=CD&Code2=3530&Data=Count&SearchText=kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |archivedate=13 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<ref name=SC06-ca>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=541&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |title=Kitchener \u2013 Cambridge \u2013 Waterloo (Census metropolitan area) |publisher=Statistics Canada |work=[[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census data]] |accessdate=12 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213163802/http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CMACA&Code1=541&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&Data=Count&SearchText=kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&TABID=1 |archivedate=13 February 2017 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=SC06/><ref name=SC06-ca/><ref>{{cite web |title=Census Profile, 2016 Census |url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/census-recensement/2016/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=POPC&Code1=0419&Geo2=PR&Code2=35&SearchText=Kitchener&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&B1=All&GeoLevel=PR&GeoCode=0419&TABID=1&type=0 |website=Statistics Canada |publisher=Statistics Canada |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|population_urban  = 470015 ([[List of the 100 largest municipalities in Canada by population|10th]])\n|population_metro  = 523,894 ([[List of the 100 largest metropolitan areas in Canada|10th]])\n|population_density_urban_km2 = 1745.8\n|population_density_metro_km2 = 480.1\n|postal_code_type       = [[Canadian postal code#Forward sortation areas|Forward sortation area]]\n|postal_code            = [[List of N postal codes of Canada|N2A to N2H, N2M to N2R]]\n|area_codes         = [[Area codes 519, 226 and 548|519, 226 and 548]]\n|timezone          = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|EST]]\n|utc_offset        = \u22125\n|coordinates       = {{coord|43|25|07|N|80|28|22|W|region:CA-ON|display=inline,title}}\n|timezone_DST      = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n|utc_offset_DST    = \u22124\n|blank1_name = [[Geographical Names Board of Canada|GNBC]] Code\n|blank1_info = FEBWC<ref name=\"GNBC\">{{cite web | title = Kitchener | publisher = Natural Resources Canada | date = October 6, 2016 | url = http://www4.rncan.gc.ca/search-place-names/unique/FEBWC}}</ref>\n|website           = [http://www.kitchener.ca/ www.kitchener.ca]\n|footnotes         =\t\n|population_demonym= Kitchenerite\n\n}}\n\n'''Kitchener''' is a city in the [[Regional Municipality of Waterloo]], [[Ontario]]. Located approximately {{convert|100|km|mi|abbr=on}} west of [[Toronto]], Kitchener is the regional seat. Kitchener was called '''[[Berlin to Kitchener name change|Berlin]]''' until 1916; it was designated the Town of Berlin from 1854 until 1912 and the City of Berlin from 1912 until 1916.\n\nThe City of Kitchener covers an area of 136.86 square kilometres and had a population of 233,222 at the time of the [[Canada 2016 Census|2016 Census]]. The Kitchener [[Tri-Cities (Ontario)|metropolitan area]], which includes the smaller, neighbouring cities of [[Waterloo, Ontario|Waterloo]] to the north and [[Cambridge, Ontario|Cambridge]] to the south, has 523,894 people, making it the tenth largest [[Census Metropolitan Area]] (CMA) in Canada and the fourth largest CMA in Ontario.\n\nKitchener and Waterloo are considered \"twin cities\" which are often referred to jointly as \"Kitchener\u2013Waterloo\" (K\u2013W), although they have separate [[Municipal government in Canada|municipal governments]]. Including Cambridge, the three cities are known as \"[[Tri-Cities (Ontario)|the Tri-Cities]]\". All are part of the Regional Municipality of Waterloo, which was created in 1973, when it replaced Waterloo County, which had been created in 1853.\n\n==Geography and climate==\n\n===Geography===\nKitchener is located in [[Southwestern Ontario]], in the [[Saint Lawrence Lowlands]]. This geological and climatic region has wet-climate soils and deciduous forests. Situated in the Grand River Valley, the area is generally above {{convert|300|m|ft|abbr=on|sigfig=1}} in elevation.\n\nKitchener is the largest city within the [[Grand River (Ontario)|Grand River]] watershed, and the largest city on the Haldimand Tract. Just to the west of the city is [[Baden Hill]], in [[Wilmot, Ontario|Wilmot Township]]. This glacial [[kame]] remnant formation is the highest elevation for many miles. The other dominant glacial feature is the [[Waterloo Moraine]], which snakes its way through the region and holds a significant quantity of [[artesian wells]], from which the city derives most of its drinking water. The settlement's first name, Sandhills, is an accurate description of the higher points of the moraine.\n\n===Climate===\nKitchener has a [[humid continental climate]] of the warm summer subtype (''Dfb'' under the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]); there are large seasonal differences, usually warm and humid summers and cold to occasionally very cold winters. Winter-like conditions generally last from the mid-December until mid-March, while summer temperatures generally occur between mid-May to close to the end of September.\n\nMarch 2012 went down in the history books for Kitchener \u2013 between 16 and 22 March, temperatures ranged from {{convert|21.4|C|F|1}} to {{convert|27.0|C|F|1}}\u20147 record highs in a row. 19 March high of {{convert|24|C|F|1}} is one of the highest winter temperatures ever recorded, while 22 March high of {{convert|27|C|F|1}} is the highest for March in this area.\n\nTemperatures during the year can exceed {{convert|30|C|F|1}} in the summer and drop below {{convert|-20|C|F|1}} in the winter several times a year, but prolonged periods of extreme temperatures are rare.  The frost-free period for Kitchener averages about 147 frost-free days a year,<ref name=climate /> a much lower number than cities on the Great Lakes due its inland location and higher elevation. Snowfall averages {{convert|160|cm|in|0}}  per year; this is high, but not nearly as high as areas more directly affected by [[lake effect snow]].\n\nThe highest temperature ever recorded in Kitchener was {{convert|38.3|C|0}} on August 6 & 7, 1918, and again on July 27, 1941.<ref name=\"August 1918\"/><ref name=\"July 1941\"/> The coldest temperature ever recorded was {{convert|-34.1|C|1}} on February 16, 2015.<ref name=\"February 2015\"/>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = [[Region of Waterloo International Airport]], 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1914\u2013present{{efn|Daily maximum and minimum temperatures and precipitation were recorded at Kitchener from October 1914 to December 1977 and at [[Region of Waterloo International Airport]] from March 1970 to present.<ref name=\"Kitchener\"/><ref name=\"climate\"/>}}\n|metric first = Y\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high C = 14.2\n|Feb record high C = 16.8\n|Mar record high C = 27.0\n|Apr record high C = 30.0\n|May record high C = 33.3\n|Jun record high C = 36.7\n|Jul record high C = 38.3\n|Aug record high C = 38.3\n|Sep record high C = 36.7\n|Oct record high C = 31.1\n|Nov record high C = 25.0\n|Dec record high C = 18.7\n|year rec