ip, Pennsylvania|Bensalem]], Pennsylvania.\n*2019 - Brian Smart, 25, [[Hatboro, Pennsylvania|Hatboro]], [[Pennsylvania]], was an athletic trainer at [[Upper Darby High School]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Broad Street Run}}\n* [http://www.broadstreetrun.com Broad Street Run official site]\n\n{{10-mile road races}}\n\n[[Category:10-mile runs]]\n[[Category:Sports in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Road running competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1980]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Blue Cross]] '''Broad Street Run''', which has taken place in [[Philadelphia]] on the first Sunday in May since the early 1980s, is the largest (40,689 runners in 2012<ref>[http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2011/05/01/beautiful-weather-makes-for-a-perfect-day-for-the-annual-broad-street-run/ Beautiful Weather Makes For A Perfect Day For The Annual Broad Street Run]. CBS Philly (May 1, 2011). Retrieved on 2012-1-10.</ref>) 10-mile road race in the [[United States]].\n\n==Course==\nThe race starts at T.S. Park, in the [[Logan, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania|Logan neighborhood]], on the front lawn of historic [[Einstein Medical Center|Einstein Medical Center Philadelphia]] and at the athletic fields at [[Central High School (Philadelphia)|Central High School]]. The course stretches south along [[Broad Street (Philadelphia)|Broad Street]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadstreetrun.com/Assets/BSR+Course+Map+2.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708095122/http://www.broadstreetrun.com/Assets/BSR%2BCourse%2BMap%2B2.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-08 }}</ref>  Runners pass [[Temple University]], [[Roman Catholic High School for Boys]], [[Philadelphia City Hall|City Hall]], [[Pennsylvania Academy of the Fine Arts]], and the [[Kimmel Center for the Performing Arts|Kimmel Center]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitphilly.com/sports/philadelphia/blue-cross-broad-street-run-10-miler/|title=Blue Cross Broad Street Run|publisher=}}</ref>  The race finishes at the [[Philadelphia Naval Shipyard|Navy Yard]] in [[South Philadelphia]].  Due in part to its nearly flat (actually slightly downhill) route, it has become a favorite in the running community for those working to establish personal best times. All finishers receive a medal.\n\n==History==\nThe race was first run in 1980 with 1454 men and 122 women finishing.  In that year and in 1981, participants ran straight through the courtyard of City Hall; since then, runners are diverted around the building.  \n\nUntil 1989, the race ended with a lap around the field at [[JFK Stadium]] in South Philadelphia.  After the stadium was condemned and demolished, the finish moved to [[FDR Park]] (on the other side of Broad Street), and then to the Navy Yard, about a quarter mile beyond the front gates.\n\nParticipation rose steadily through the 1990s and exploded by the mid-2000s. Since 2013, registration of single runners (though not teams) has been handled by lottery, with about 40,000 entrants, and roughly 35,000 runners finishing the race, the majority of them women.<ref>http://www.broadstreetrun.com/News/Documents/Race%20Information%20Guide%20Final%204-27-14.pdf</ref>\n\n==Course records==\n* Open Male: Patrick Cheruiyot, 45:14, 2007<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadstreetrun.com/media.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-12-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229183955/http://www.broadstreetrun.com/media.htm |archivedate=2008-12-29 }}</ref>\n* Open Female: [[Catherine Ndereba]], 53:07, 1999\n* Master Male: Andrey Kuznetsov, 50:13, 2002\n* Master Female: Sandra Mewett, 57:56, 1992\n* Open Wheelchair Male: Tony Nogueira, 32:05, 2007\n* Open Wheelchair Female: Jessica Galli, 35:59, 2001\n* Master Wheelchair Male: Tony Nogueira, 33:52, 2008\n* Master Wheelchair Female: Jacqui Kapinowski, 49:19, 2008\n\n==Past 