te|[[Crystal Burnick]]|USA}}\n|57:07\n|-\n|38th\n|2017\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Dominic Korir]]|KEN}}\n|47:38\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Askale Merachi]]|ETH}}\n|53:49\n|-\n|39th\n|2018\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Daniel Kemoi]]|KEN}}\n|45:43\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Sophy Jepchirchir]]|USA}}\n|55:43\n|-\n|40th\n|2019\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Daniel Kemoi]]|KEN}}\n|47:20\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|[[Susan Jerotich]]|KEN}}\n|54:47\n|}\n\n'''Winners by Country'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-|-\n! Number\n! Country\n! Last Time\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 36\n|| [[United States]]\n|| 2018\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 28\n|| [[Kenya]]\n|| 2019\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 9\n|| [[Ethiopia]]\n|| 2017\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 3\n|| [[Morocco]]\n|| 2014\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 2\n|| [[Russia]]\n|| 2006\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1\n|| [[Tanzania]]\n|| 1992\n|}\n\n==Top Philadelphia Finsher (Richard Lagocki Memorial Award)==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!class=unsortable|Edition\n!Year\n!class=unsortable|Men's winner\n!Time ([[hour|h]]:[[minute|m]]:[[second|s]])\n!class=unsortable|Women's winner\n!Time ([[hour|h]]:[[minute|m]]:[[second|s]])\n|-\n|5th\n|1984\n|align=left|{{flagathlete||USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Lena Holman|USA}}\n|59:58\n|-\n|7th\n|1986\n|align=left|{{flagathlete||USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Renie Shields|USA}}\n|57:27\n|-\n|8th\n|1987\n|align=left|{{flagathlete||USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Renie Shields|USA}}\n|57:51\n|-\n|21st\n|2000\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Rick McGarry|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Andrea Niggemeier|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|22nd\n|2001\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Rick McGarry|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Andrea Niggemeier|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|23rd\n|2002\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Bob Schwelm|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Abby Dean|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|24th\n|2003\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Matt DiPretore|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Abby Dean|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|25th\n|2004\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Matt Byrne|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Andrea Niggemeier|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|26th\n|2005\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Tom Haxton|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Veena Reddy|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|27th\n|2006\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Tom Haxton|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Emily Kroshus|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|28th\n|2007\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Macharia Yuot|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Renee Gunning|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|29th\n|2008\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Tom Haxton|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Abby Dean|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|30th\n|2009\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Tom Haxton|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Sheila Klick|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|31st\n|2010\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Gregory Bielecki|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Emily McGregor|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|32nd\n|2011\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Gregory Bielecki|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Claire Hewitt|USA}}\n| \n|-\n|33rd\n|2012\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Gregory Bielecki|USA}}\n| \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Abby Dean|USA}}\n|1:02:30\n|-\n|34th\n|2013\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Paul Matuszak|USA}}\n|51:11 \n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Lauren Kelly|USA}}\n|59:23\n|-\n|35th\n|2014\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Geraint Davies|USA}}\n|51:06\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Catherine Campbell|USA}}\n|1:01:46 \n|-\n|36th\n|2015\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Stephen Schelander|USA}}\n|50:27\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Claire Hewitt|USA}}\n|58:33 \n|-\n|37th\n|2016\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Justin Garrard|USA}}\n|50:07\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Jessica Fragola|USA}}\n|58:12 \n|-\n|38th\n|2017\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Patrick Richie|USA}}\n|49:44\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Margaret Vido|USA}}\n|56:56 \n|-\n|39th\n|2018\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Duriel Hardy|USA}}  \n|49:31\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Margaret Vido|USA}}  \n|57:01 \n|-\n|40th\n|2019\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Paul Matuszak|USA}}\n|49:21\n|align=left|{{flagathlete|Samantha Roecker|USA}}\n|55:38\n|}\n\n==Deaths==\n*1998 - Richard Lagocki, 45, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania<ref>[https://archive.today/20130125061555/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-19713875.html Kenyan wins Broad Street Run]. AP (May 3, 1998). Retrieved on 2011-10-13.</ref>\n*2007 - Robert A. Massaroni, 29, [[Holland, Pennsylvania|Holland]], [[Pennsylvania]], was a 7th grade Social Studies teacher at Shafer Middle School in [[Bensalem Township, Pennsylvania|Bensalem]], Pennsylvania.\n*2019 - Brian Smart, 25, [[Hatboro, Pennsylvania|Hatboro]], [[Pennsylvania]], was an athletic trainer at [[Upper Darby High School]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Broad Street Run}}\n* [http://www.broadstreetrun.com Broad Street Run official site]\n\n{{10-mile road races}}\n\n[[Category:10-mile runs]]\n[[Category:Sports in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Road running competitions in the United States]]\n[[Category:Recurring sporting events established in 1980]]\n", "name_user": "Cnwilliams", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Mike Bradley\u2192Mike Bradley (athlete)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broad_Street_Run"}
{"title_page": "Norman Hossack", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{Autobiography|date=March 2015}}{{Notability|bio|date=March 2015}}{{Underlinked|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Norman Hugh Hossack''' is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] inventor and engineer, who invented the Hossack motorcycle front suspension system, used on some [[BMW Motorrad]] K series motorcycles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bmw-motorrad.com/com/en/index.html?content=http://www.bmw-motorrad.com/com/en/technology_new/item_duolever.html&notrack=1 |title=BMW Motorrad International |publisher=Bmw-motorrad.com |date=2015-02-09 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cameron |first1=Kevin |title=Back to the Future |magazine=[[Cycle World]] |date=January 2004|volume=43 |issue=7 |page=45}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Holmstron Nelson |first1=Darwin & Brian |title=BMW Motorcycles |date=2009 |publisher=Motorbooks |isbn=9780760337486 |page=177}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2018}}\nNorman Hossack was born in [[Bellshill]], Scotland, and grew up in [[Rhodesia]]. Hossack's father, also an inventor, developed methods to pump [[water in Africa]]. Hossack's grandfather built and patented dry cell batteries as far back as 1910.\n  \nHossack learned to ride motorcycles at a young age on the uncluttered roads of Rhodesia. His first bikes were a [[BSA Bantam]], a Greeves scrambler and a [[Ducati Mach 1|Ducati 250 Mach 1]], which he raced. This racing bug took Hossack to the [[Isle of Man TT]] in 1969. The following year Hossack worked as mechanic for fellow Rhodesian and Manx winner Gordon Keith on a tour of the Continental racing circus. Hossack's talents were spotted by young [[Barry Sheene]] who offered him a job, but Hossack took a job with [[McLaren|Bruce McLaren Motor Racing]] in 1972. Hossack spent the next three years learning his craft and honing his skills as chassis builder, mechanic, and pit crew member. Hossack worked 3 years on the Indy team, and in 1974 McLaren won the [[Indy 500]], and the [[Formula One|F1]] championship. He was later involved with other motor racing projects including 3 stints at the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]], twice as race planner and manager.\n\n==Inventions==\nHossack's first invention was his 2 stroke engine, inspired by the [[Wankel engine]] which was the holy grail of the automobile industry at the time. The first Hossack prototype engine was built in 1973 and was run in the McLaren work shop. The second engine, a more serious build is still a runner today.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Crowe |url=http://thekneeslider.com/the-hossack-engine-a-square-piston-two-stroke/ |title=The Hossack Engine \u2013 a Square Piston Two Stroke |website=Thekneeslider.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref>\n\nThe Hossack suspension system came into being in the years after Hossack left McLaren. It started with some sketches then moved to a wire coat hanger experiment. The next step was to turn it into metal which became Hossack 1, a championship winning racer.\n\nIn 2001, Hossack moved to the USA designing scanners used in the medical industry. Hossack's name is on several patents in the medical devices industry. These IVUS scanners (Intra Vascular Ultrasound) are used to see inside the vessels around the heart.\n\nIn 2010, Hossack turned his thinking to mountain bikes. Teased by his work mates in the Medical company he worked in he took up the challenge. The motive here was to create an attachment to a standard bicycle frame rather than a Hossack type suspension system.\n\n==Hossack suspension system==\nThe Hossack front suspension system consists of 2 wish-bones, an upright and steering linkage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Foale|first1=Tony |title=Motorcycle Chassis Design|date=1984 |publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd |isbn=085045560X |pages=91\u201393}}</ref> Similar components are found on the front of all racing cars, the only significant difference being in the up-right which has its geometry rearranged. The wish-bones look and work exactly like their racing car equivalent. The up-right performs the same task as its racing car equivalent but has its axle rotated through 90 degrees and over hung. The steering link does the same job as its name sake in car suspension. There is a handle bar pivot but this carries none of the suspension loading and only has to handle the weight of the rider's upper half. The spring/damper element can be run in several different positions to achieve different conditions as is also common in the racing car world.\n\n==Racers==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2018}}\nAfter leaving McLaren, Hossack started on motorcycle design, applying his accumulated knowledge to the design of his first machine, developing a unique front suspension system which he formulated using a wire coat hanger and a piece of wood. Wheels and parts were sourced from a scrap yard to build a rudimentary test-bed, and finally an XL500 Honda engine was donated by a friend. Although built only to test the theory, this very bike proved successful enough to graduate to the race track. Updated with Astralite wheels, it later went on to win the British Single Cylinder Championship in 1986,<ref>''Motorcycle Sport'', March 1987, pp.123-124. ''Single cylinder road racing''. Accessed 22 July 2018</ref> 1987 and 1988 ridden by Vernon Glashier, who still owns the bike.\n\nBy late 1982{{contradict-inline|date=July 2018|reason=Chronology of the prose does not make sense, implying the first build was later than the third}} the third Hossack bike was ready to race and was designed to fit the 350cc Yamaha TZ and RD engines. During 1983 several well-known journalists had ridden Hossack 3, including Alan Cathcart, Ray Knight and Mat Oxley. Hossack went on to build more versions of his design for other engines which include Ducati, Suzuki and Laverda.\n\n==BMW K100==\nFinding club racing changing towards production models Hossack next turned his hand to street models - first the PDQ Kawasaki<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cathcart |first1=Alan |title=Dream Bikes, First Edition |publisher=Macdonald Orbis |isbn=0356155668 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dreambikes0000cath/page/202 202\u2013707] |url=https://archive.org/details/dreambikes0000cath/page/202 }}</ref> and later a BMW K100. Hossack set himself the task with the K100 to use as many standard parts as practical and make it handle and stop better. In the process the final product was {{cvt|12|lb}} lighter than the standard unit, and possessed all the advantages that BMW later claimed for the K series bikes. This Hossack-BMW conversion was popular in Germany where the design received a TUV type-approval for sale. One of Hossack's conversions was taken to BMW's headquarters in Munich where it was shown to their management and run on their test track. Unfortunately for Hossack, BMW were in the final stages of releasing their Telelever suspension system.{{vague|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Triumph conversion==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2018}}\nHossack's last bike conversion was a [[Triumph Trident|Triumph Trident 900]] in 1994, commissioned by Formula 1 entrepreneur [[Keith Duckworth]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burr |first1=Norman |title=First principles : the official biography of Keith Duckworth OBE |isbn=978-1-845845-28-5 |pages=289, 297, 300}}</ref> This proved to be an ideal application, as the cylinder heads of the triple offered an ideal mounting point for the lower wishbone. The conversion worked well but never went further than that one prototype.\n\n==Post motorcycles==\nDuring the 1990s, after leaving the motorcycle design world behind, Hossack spent several years inventing machines for the packaging industry before taking a position in the medical device industry. He was involved in designing IVUS scanners which are used to visualize the vessels around the heart. That company called IRL was bought out,{{by whom|date=July 2018}} and the new company moved Hossack and his family to the US.\n\nFollowing his move to California in 2001, Hossack applied his inventiveness and engineering skills developing devices for the medical field, specializing in IVUS (Intra Vascular Ultra Sound) and is named on several patents in this field. During this time he also designed a mountain bike suspension system<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Crowe |url=http://thekneeslider.com/norman-hossack-builds-a-mountain-bike-suspension/ |title=Norman Hossack Builds a Mountain Bike Suspension |publisher=Thekneeslider.com |date=2013-08-27 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref> and applied his front suspension system to a Ducati SS 800.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Crowe |url=http://thekneeslider.com/norman-hossack-engineers-a-trellis-front-suspension-on-a-trellis-frame-ducati/ |title=Norman Hossack Engineers a Trellis Front Suspension on a Trellis Frame Ducati 800 |publisher=Thekneeslider.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.motorradonline.de/vermischtes/reportage-das-leben-von-norman-hossack/523236 |title=Reportage Das Leben von Norman Hossack - Motorradnachrichten - MOTORRAD |publisher=Motorradonline.de |date=2014-01-30 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |first1=Darwin |last1=Holmstrom |first2= Brian J. |last2=Nelson |title=BMW Motorcycles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yQnrSn8nNVUC&pg=PA177 |publisher=MotorBooks International |isbn=978-1-61673-102-1 |pages=177\u2013}}\n*{{cite book |magazine=[[Cycle World]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VYB28ExdkSMC&pg=RA6-PA45|date=July 2004 |page=45 |last=Cameron |first=Kevin |title= Back to the Future; Before there was Duolever, there was Norman Hossack |issn=0011-4286}}\n*{{cite book|first=Tony |last=Foale |title=Motorcycle Handling and Chassis Design: The Art and Science |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=84hF-qoR5I8C&pg=SA7-PA23 |year=2006 |publisher=Tony Foale |isbn=978-84-933286-3-4 |pages=7\u2013}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Burr |first1=Norman |title=First principles : the official biography of Keith Duckworth OBE |isbn=978-1-845845-28-5 |pages=289, 297, 300}}\n*{{cite magazine |last= Knight|first=Ray |date= June 1984|title=The Hossack\u2014A new British racer. Of frames and things; discussing, then testing, the Hossack chassis |magazine=Motorcycle Sport |location= |publisher=|pages=271-273}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hossack, Norman Hugh}}\n[[Category:British motorcycle designers]]\n[[Category:Scottish motorsport people]]\n[[Category:People from Bellshill]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{Autobiography|date=March 2015}}{{Notability|bio|date=March 2015}}{{Underlinked|date=February 2015}}\n}}\n\n'''Norman Hugh Hossack''' is a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] inventor and engineer, who invented the Hossack motorcycle front suspension system, used on some [[BMW Motorrad]] K series motorcycles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bmw-motorrad.com/com/en/index.html?content=http://www.bmw-motorrad.com/com/en/technology_new/item_duolever.html&notrack=1 |title=BMW Motorrad International |publisher=Bmw-motorrad.com |date=2015-02-09 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cameron |first1=Kevin |title=Back to the Future |magazine=[[Cycle World]] |date=January 2004|volume=43 |issue=7 |page=45}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Holmstron Nelson |first1=Darwin & Brian |title=BMW Motorcycles |date=2009 |publisher=Motorbooks |isbn=9780760337486 |page=177}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2018}}\nNorman Hossack was born in [[Bellshill]], Scotland, and grew up in [[Rhodesia]]. Hossack's father, also an inventor, developed methods to pump [[water in Africa]]. Hossack's grandfather built and patented dry cell batteries as far back as 1910.\n  \nHossack learned to ride motorcycles at a young age on the uncluttered roads of Rhodesia. His first bikes were a [[BSA Bantam]], a Greeves scrambler and a [[Ducati Mach 1|Ducati 250 Mach 1]], which he raced. This racing bug took Hossack to the [[Isle of Man TT]] in 1969. The following year Hossack worked as mechanic for fellow Rhodesian and Manx winner Gordon Keith on a tour of the Continental racing circus. Hossack's talents were spotted by young [[Barry Sheene]] who offered him a job, but Hossack took a job with [[McLaren|Bruce McLaren Motor Racing]] in 1972. Hossack spent the next three years learning his craft and honing his skills as chassis builder, mechanic, and pit crew member. Hossack worked 3 years on the Indy team, and in 1974 McLaren won the [[Indy 500]], and the [[Formula One|F1]] championship. He was later involved with other motor racing projects including 3 stints at the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]], twice as race planner and manager.\n\n==Inventions==\nHossack's first invention was his 2 stroke engine, inspired by the [[Wankel engine]] which was the holy grail of the automobile industry at the time. The first Hossack prototype engine was built in 1973 and was run in the McLaren work shop. The second engine, a more serious build is still a runner today.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Crowe |url=http://thekneeslider.com/the-hossack-engine-a-square-piston-two-stroke/ |title=The Hossack Engine \u2013 a Square Piston Two Stroke |website=Thekneeslider.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref>\n\nThe Hossack suspension system came into being in the years after Hossack left McLaren. It started with some sketches then moved to a wire coat hanger experiment. The next step was to turn it into metal which became Hossack 1, a championship winning racer.\n\nIn 2001, Hossack moved to the USA designing scanners used in the medical industry. Hossack's name is on several patents in the medical devices industry. These IVUS scanners (Intra Vascular Ultrasound) are used to see inside the vessels around the heart.\n\nIn 2010, Hossack turned his thinking to mountain bikes. Teased by his work mates in the Medical company he worked in he took up the challenge. The motive here was to create an attachment to a standard bicycle frame rather than a Hossack type suspension system.\n\n==Hossack suspension system==\nThe Hossack front suspension system consists of 2 wish-bones, an upright and steering linkage.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Foale|first1=Tony |title=Motorcycle Chassis Design|date=1984 |publisher=Osprey Publishing Ltd |isbn=085045560X |pages=91\u201393}}</ref> Similar components are found on the front of all racing cars, the only significant difference being in the up-right which has its geometry rearranged. The wish-bones look and work exactly like their racing car equivalent. The up-right performs the same task as its racing car equivalent but has its axle rotated through 90 degrees and over hung. The steering link does the same job as its name sake in car suspension. There is a handle bar pivot but this carries none of the suspension loading and only has to handle the weight of the rider's upper half. The spring/damper element can be run in several different positions to achieve different conditions as is also common in the racing car world.\n\n==Racers==\n{{BLP sources section|date=July 2018}}\nAfter leaving McLaren, Hossack started on motorcycle design, applying his accumulated knowledge to the design of his first machine, developing a unique front suspension system which he formulated using a wire coat hanger and a piece of wood. Wheels and parts were sourced from a scrap yard to build a rudimentary test-bed, and finally an XL500 Honda engine was donated by a friend. Although built only to test the theory, this very bike proved successful enough to graduate to the race track. Updated with Astralite wheels, it later went on to win the British Single Cylinder Championship in 1986,<ref>''Motorcycle Sport'', March 1987, pp.123-124. ''Single cylinder road racing''. Accessed 22 July 2018</ref> 1987 and 1988 ridden by Vernon Glashier, who still owns the bike.\n\nBy late 1982{{contradict-inline|date=July 2018|reason=Chronology of the prose does not make sense, implying the first build was later than the third}} the third Hossack bike was ready to race and was designed to fit the 350cc Yamaha TZ and RD engines. During 1983 several well-known journalists had ridden Hossack 3, including Alan Cathcart, Ray Knight and Mat Oxley. Hossack went on to build more versions of his design for other engines which include Ducati, Suzuki and Laverda.\n\n==BMW K100==\nFinding club racing changing towards production models Hossack next turned his hand to street models - first the PDQ Kawasaki<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cathcart |first1=Alan |title=Dream Bikes, First Edition |publisher=Macdonald Orbis |isbn=0356155668 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dreambikes0000cath/page/202 202\u2013707] |url=https://archive.org/details/dreambikes0000cath/page/202 }}</ref> and later a BMW K100. Hossack set himself the task with the K100 to use as many standard parts as practical and make it handle and stop better. In the process the final product was {{cvt|12|lb}} lighter than the standard unit, and possessed all the advantages that BMW later claimed for the K series bikes. This Hossack-BMW conversion was popular in Germany where the design received a TUV type-approval for sale. One of Hossack's conversions was taken to BMW's headquarters in Munich where it was shown to their management and run on their test track. Unfortunately for Hossack, BMW were in the final stages of releasing their Telelever suspension system.{{vague|date=July 2018}}\n\n==Triumph conversion==\n{{BLP unsourced section|date=July 2018}}\nHossack's last bike conversion was a [[Triumph Trident|Triumph Trident 900]] in 1994, commissioned by Formula 1 entrepreneur [[Keith Duckworth]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Burr |first1=Norman |title=First principles : the official biography of Keith Duckworth OBE |isbn=978-1-845845-28-5 |pages=289, 297, 300}}</ref> This proved to be an ideal application, as the cylinder heads of the triple offered an ideal mounting point for the lower wishbone. The conversion worked well but never went further than that one prototype.\n\n==Post motorcycles==\nDuring the 1990s, after leaving the motorcycle design world behind, Hossack spent several years inventing machines for the packaging industry before taking a position in the medical device industry. He was involved in designing IVUS scanners which are used to visualize the vessels around the heart. That company called IRL was bought out,{{by whom|date=July 2018}} and the new company moved Hossack and his family to the US.\n\nFollowing his move to California in 2001, Hossack applied his inventiveness and engineering skills developing devices for the medical field, specializing in IVUS (Intra Vascular Ultra Sound) and is named on several patents in this field. During this time he also designed a mountain bike suspension system<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Crowe |url=http://thekneeslider.com/norman-hossack-builds-a-mountain-bike-suspension/ |title=Norman Hossack Builds a Mountain Bike Suspension |publisher=Thekneeslider.com |date=2013-08-27 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref> and applied his front suspension system to a Ducati SS 800.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Crowe |url=http://thekneeslider.com/norman-hossack-engineers-a-trellis-front-suspension-on-a-trellis-frame-ducati/ |title=Norman Hossack Engineers a Trellis Front Suspension on a Trellis Frame Ducati 800 |publisher=Thekneeslider.com |date= |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.motorradonline.de/vermischtes/reportage-das-leben-von-norman-hossack/523236 |title=Reportage Das Leben von Norman Hossack - Motorradnachrichten - MOTORRAD |publisher=Motorradonline.de |date=2014-01-30 |accessdate=2015-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book |first1=Darwin |last1=Holmstrom |first2= Brian J. |last2=Nelson |title=BMW Motorcycles |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yQnrSn8nNVUC&pg=PA177 |publisher=MotorBooks International |isbn=978-1-61673-102-1 |pages=177\u2013}}\n*{{cite book |magazine=[[Cycle World]] |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VYB28ExdkSMC&pg=RA6-PA45|date=July 2004 |page=45 |last=Cameron |first=Kevin |title= Back to the Future; Before there was Duolever, there was Norman Hossack |issn=0011-4286}}\n*{{cite book|first=Tony |last=Foale |title=Motorcycle Handling and Chassis Design: The Art and Science |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=84hF-qoR5I8C&pg=SA7-PA23 |year=2006 |publisher=Tony Foale |isbn=978-84-933286-3-4 |pages=7\u2013}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Burr |first1=Norman |title=First principles : the official biography of Keith Duckworth OBE |isbn=978-1-845845-28-5 |pages=289, 297, 300}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hossack, Norman Hugh}}\n[[Category:British motorcycle designers]]\n[[Category:Scottish motorsport people]]\n[[Category:People from Bellshill]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Rocknrollmancer", "label": "safe", "comment": "add an example of further reading (in my house, not yet read it myself", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norman_Hossack"}
{"title_page": "Belgrade Main railway station", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Belgrade Centre railway station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| name          = Belgrade Main Railway Station\n| native_name   = \u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\n| native_name_lang = sr\n| type          = \n| style         = \n| image         = Beograd train station.JPG\n| image_upright = upright\n| image_caption = Station building and surroundings\n| address       = Savski trg 2, [[Belgrade]]\n| map_type            = Serbia Belgrade\n| country       = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| coordinates   = {{coord|44|48|31|N|20|27|20|E|source:kolossus-srwiki|display=inline, title}}\n| line          = \n| connections   = 100 m: [[Belgrade Bus Station]]<br>{{rint|bus|1}} 36, 46, 51, 78, 83, 91, 92, 511, 551, 552, 553, 601, A1, E1<br>{{rint|tram|1}} 2, 3, 7, 9, 12, 13\n| other         = \n| structure     = At-grade\n| platform      = 6 [[bay platform]]s\n| depth         = \n| levels        = \n| tracks        = 13\n| parking       = Yes\n| bicycle       = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened        = {{start date and age|1884|08|23|df=yes}}\n| closed        = {{end date and age|2018|06|30|df=yes}}\n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = {{start date and age|1970|05|31|df=yes}}\n| ADA           = \n| code          = \n| owned         = [[Serbian Railways]]\n| zone          = \n| smartcardname = \n| smartcardstatus = \n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = \n| map_locator   = \n}}\n\nThe '''Belgrade Main railway station''' ({{lang-sr|\u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430|\u017delezni\u010dka stanica Beograd Glavna}}) was a [[train station]] in [[Belgrade]], the capital of Serbia. It was built between 1882 and 1885 after the designs of the architect Dragutin Milutinovi\u0107, and it has the status of a [[\u0441ultural monument of great importance]].<ref name=\"beogradskonasledje.rs\">{{cite web|url=http://beogradskonasledje.rs/kd/zavod/savski_venac/zeleznicka_stanica.html |title=\u017delezni\u010dka stanica|publisher=Zavod za za\u0161titu spomenika kulture grada Beograda}}</ref> Until the opening of the new [[Belgrade Centre railway station|Belgrade Center station]] (Prokop) in 2016, it was the city's main station, and the busiest train station in the country. In order to free up the space for the [[Belgrade Waterfront]] project, the station was closed on 1 July 2018, and repurposed to become a museum.<ref>[http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/zgrada-zeljeznicke-stanice-u-beogradu-postaje-muzej Al Jazeera: Zgrada \u017eeljezni\u010dke stanice u Beogradu postaje muzej]</ref>\n\nPassenger trains have been gradually relocated to the new station during 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tanjug.rs/full-view_en.aspx?izb=225983 |title=Vucic opens Prokop railway station after 40 years |publisher=Tanjug |date=26 January 2016}}</ref> Most national railway traffic was moved to the new station in December 2017, thus leaving only international trains and two trains to Novi Sad in the old station.<ref name=\"RTS\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/drustvo/2966308/prokop-od-danas-glavna-zeleznicka-stanica.html |title=Prokop od danas glavna \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica |date=10 December 2017 |publisher=[[Radio Television of Serbia]]}}</ref> The Main station operated until 30 June 2018, when the last train, international train 340 to [[Budapest]], left the station at 21:40.<ref name=\"kaput\">{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Oti\u0161ao poslednji voz | trans-title = The last train has left | newspaper = Politika | page = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 1 July 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/406527/Otisao-poslednji-voz-FOTO }}</ref> International trains were relocated to Prokop and train to Bar relocated to the [[Top\u010dider railway station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/404201/Radovi-na-prugama-obimniji-nego-prethodnih-25-godina |title=Radovi na prugama obimniji nego prethodnih 25 godina|first=Goran |last=Volf|publisher=[[Politika]]|date=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Origin ===\n\nAt the 1878 [[Congress of Berlin]] the Principality of Serbia was [[de jure]] recognized as an independent state. The great powers of the day decided that Serbia should construct the railway. Not economically developed to begin with, Serbia was additionally pauperized after the [[Serbian\u2013Ottoman War (1876\u20131878)|Serbian-Ottoman wars]] from 1876 to 1878, so it lacked the necessary funds. Prince [[Milan Obrenovi\u0107 IV|Milan Obrenovi\u0107]] and the government announced a [[request for tender]] and the bidding was won by a French company. According to a popular - but unproven - version of events, Prince Milan accepted a bribe of 1 million francs in gold to give the job to the French.<ref name=\"Politika\">{{Citation | author = Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = Gvozdeni konji u Ciganskoj bari | newspaper = [[Politika]]-Magazin, No. 1039 | pages = 28\u201329 | language = Serbian | date = 27 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\nThe concession included the construction of the [[Belgrade\u2013Ni\u0161 railway]], the train bridge over the [[Sava]] river and a railway that would connect Belgrade to [[Zemun]], a border town of [[Austria-Hungary]] at the time. The location of the future station building was chosen in 1881.<ref name=tajne>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = Tajne Glavne \u017eelezni\u010dke stanice | trans-title = Secrets of the Main Railway Station | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 16 April 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/427585/Tajne-Glavne-zeleznicke-stanice}}</ref> It was a marshy [[bog]] called ''Ciganska bara'' (\"Gypsy pond\").<ref name=Politika/> The bog was charted for the first time in an [[Austria]]n map from 1789. It was a marsh which covered a wide area stretching from the present-day ''Kara\u0111or\u0111eva'' street to the mouth of the [[Top\u010diderska Reka]] into the Sava, across the northern tip of [[Ada Ciganlija]]. The marshy area covered the today's location of the Belgrade Main railway station and parts of the ''Sarajevska'' and ''Hajduk-Veljkov venac'' streets. Ciganska bara drained two other bogs. One  was located on [[Slavija Square|Slavija]], which drained through the creek of ''Vra\u010darski potok''<ref>{{Citation | author = Dragana Joki\u0107 Stamenkovi\u0107| title = Beograd na dvesta sputanih voda| newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 28 May 2011 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/178840/Beograd-na-dvesta-sputanih-voda }}</ref> which flew down the area of the today's [[Nemanjina Street]]. The other pond was [[Zeleni Venac]]. The eponymous [[Gypsies]] inhabiting the area used the mud from the bog to make roof tiles. They lived in small huts or caravans (called \"\u010derge\"), between the high grass and [[Juncaceae|rush]], with their horses and water buffalos grazing freely in the area. As most of the huts were actually [[stilt house]]s built on [[deep foundation|piles]] due to the marshy land, the area was gradually named [[Bara Venecija]] (\"[[Venice]] pond\").<ref name=ack>{{Citation | author = Dragoljub Ackovi\u0107| title = \u0160est vekova Roma u Beogradu \u2013 part XV, Veselje do kasno u no\u0107 | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAs such, the location was absolutely inappropriate for any construction work and the marsh had to be filled first. The remains of the demolished [[Republic Square (Belgrade)#Stambol Gate|Stambol Gate]] in 1866 also finished in the bog.<ref name=tajne/> By 1884 the bog was drained and buried under the rubble from all parts of the city but especially from [[Prokop (Belgrade)|Prokop]],<ref name=ack/> Prokop is located in the eastern section of the former neighborhood of [[Jatagan Mala]]. Previously, it was a geographical reference, as the area was located in the lower valley of the now-underground stream of [[Mokrolu\u0161ki Potok]]. Earth and gravel were dug and used to cover and drain the swamps on the right bank of the Sava, so that the neighborhoods of [[Savamala]] and [[Bara Venecija]] could be constructed, along with the building of central railway station. After the works were completed, the area around Mokrolu\u0161ki Potok was left as a steep, elongated cut in the ground, thus acquiring its name (Serbian ''prokop'', cut or dug through). Prince Milan personally suggested this area, which stretched above [[\u0110or\u0111e Vajfert]]'s brewery and the neighborhood of [[Mostar interchange#Neighborhood|Smutekovac]]. Among his many reasons he cited the quality of the earth and the fact that the proximity of the construction site would reduce the transportation costs. However, that land belonged to his wife, [[Natalie of Serbia|Princess Natalie]], so the prince even earned money from the station's construction. In a historical twist, Prokop is the location of Belgrade's designated present-day central railway station.<ref name=Politika/>\n\nWhen the location was chosen, it was also disconnected from Belgrade in terms of transportation. The former village of Savamala was closest, but the city could only be reached using a [[fiaker]], and this along a bypass route leading through Spomeni\u010dka Street (modern Nemanjina).<ref name=tajne/>\n\nThe construction of the railway and station initially met with fierce opposition. The law on railway construction barely passed in the National Assembly of Serbia, while for the railway itself it was said that it was both costly and unnecessary; a \"devil's snake\"; a \"destroyer of the people\", a threat to female fertility and a conduit of infiltration by foreign powers.<ref>{{cite news | author = Darko Pejovi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0418\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0435\u043c\u043d\u0435 \u043a\u0443\u045b\u0435 \u0443 \u043f\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0443 | trans-title = From ground floor house to five-floor villa | newspaper = Politika | page = 11 | language = Serbian | date = 28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Belgrade Main railway station}}\n\n=== Opening ===\n\nThe [[foundation stone]]s were laid by prince Milan: for the railway on {{OldStyleDate|3 July|1881|21 June}}, for the station on {{OldStyleDate|15 April|1883|3 April}}. The building of the station lagged behind the construction of the railway and the bridge, so when the time came for the first train to pass through Belgrade, the object wasn't finished. As it was obvious that the station won't be finished on time, the temporary object was built to serve the purpose instead. Even though at one point in 1884 it was recorded that 5,575 workers were employed on the building's construction, it couldn't be finished in time.<ref name=obnova>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u041e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0435 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0435 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435 | trans-title = Reconstruction of the former building of the Main railway station | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 6 August 2019 }}</ref> It had to be ceremonially open, even though it was still covered with scaffolds.<ref name=Politika/> The first train from this station departed towards [[Zemun]] with courtly honours, on {{OldStyleDate|1 September|1884|20 August}}, at 3 p.m.<ref>Srpske novine, 21 August 1884</ref> As Serbia was declared a kingdom in 1882, the first passengers were now King Milan, Queen Natalie and the Crown Prince [[Aleksandar Obrenovi\u0107|Alexander]], on the way to [[Vienna]]. More than 200 foreign guests and couple of thousands of citizens attended the opening ceremony.<ref>[http://arhiva.24sata.rs/vesti/beograd/vest/na-mestu-zeleznicke-stanice-pre-dva-veka-bila-je-bara/31459.phtml \u201eNa mestu \u017eelezni\u010dke stanice pre dva veka bila je bara\u201c, 24 Sata], 5 March 2012.</ref>\n\nMilitary orchestra played music all the way until the train crossed the bridge. Three days later the station was again decorated with flags and flowers as the railway to Ni\u0161 was open and the first, promotional composition towards Ni\u0161 departed. Cannons from the [[Belgrade Fortress]] marked the occasion while the military orchestras played marches. The journal ''Novi beogradski dnevnik'' wrote: \"Young and old, rich and poor, pretty and ugly, they all gathered in Bara Venecija to see the start of the first Serbian railway\". The first train departed at 8:45, with 100 passengers in nine cars with three classes. Just to accommodate the huge crowds of journalists and cheering citizens, another train departed just five minutes later.<ref name=Politika/>\n\nThe first passenger line started on {{OldStyleDate|16 September|1884|4 September}} at 8:30. It was a line to Ni\u0161, and the train had 20 cars with 200 passengers.<ref name=adio>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Od sve\u010darskih topova do \"A sad, adio\" | trans-title = From ceremonial cannons to \"And now, adio\" | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 5 September 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/437263/Od-svecarskih-topova-do-A-sad-adio}}</ref> On the same day, the line to [[Budapest|Pest]] was established, and at the beginning only two trains a day departed on these lines.<ref>Srpske novine, 2 September 1884</ref> Archbishop of Belgrade and Metropolitan of Serbia, Teodosije Mraovi\u0107, blessed the two first locomotives. The regular traffic was established 10 days later.<ref name=adio/> Until the station was finished, a small building in front of it functioned as a temporary facility (ticket booths, administration, etc.). On that spot, today is exhibited a steam locomotive, just in front of the building.<ref name=\"Politika\"/> The fully finished station became operational on 21 September 1885.<ref name=obnova/>\n\nAt the time, the central section of the building was occupied by the offices of the station's personnel, [[telephone exchange]], [[telegraph]], cashier boxes, wardrobes and police offices. The left wing of the station was adapted into the royal waiting room, while the right one was for the regular passenger. In this section there were also restaurants, while the upper floor was occupied by the living quarters for the station's employees.<ref name=adio/>\n\n=== Later developments ===\n\nAfter being completed in September 1885 and soon became the most important railway hub in this part of Europe. In 1888 it became a stop on the [[Orient Express]] route and in 1892 a ceremonial reception for [[Nikola Tesla]] was organized. The very first car in Belgrade arrived by train, via the main station, on 3 April 1903.<ref>{{cite news | author = Goran Vesi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u045b\u0430\u0458\u043d\u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a \u0443 \u043b\u0438\u043a\u0443 \u041c\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u0443\u0441\u0430 | trans-title = First traffic sign was shaped like Mickey Mouse | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 5 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=zlatno>{{Citation |author= Dejan Aleksi\u0107 |title= A vozovi prolaze - 133 godine |newspaper= Politika |page= 16 |language= Serbian |date= 4 September 2017 }}</ref> The building originally had a gas lighting, which was later replaced with the electrical one. As it was a major consumer, it was decided that the building will have its own power generator.  A mini electrical plant was built next to the station building  in 1909 and demolished in 1929, when the building of the Post Office No. 6 was built instead.<ref name=tajne/>\n\nAfter the station was finished, the area to the east developed into the square which, due to its location close both to the railway and the port, served for the transshipment of the goods, especially the cereals and grains, so in time it was named ''\u017ditni trg'' (\"Grains square\"). It was also well connected with the roads which lead outside of the city. It was directly connected with the road which is today the ''Savska'' Street in the direction of the [[Mostar interchange|Mostar]] neighborhood. There, it was splitting in two directions, one to the east (later neighborhoods of [[Jatagan Mala]] and [[Prokop (Belgrade)|Prokop]]) in the direction of [[Kragujevac]] in central Serbia, and the other to the south (neighborhoods of [[Senjak]], [[\u010cukarica]], [[\u017darkovo]]) and further to the west Serbia. The square was renamed ''Vilsonov trg'' (\"Wilson's Square\") after World War I, in honor of the US president [[Woodrow Wilson]] and today in named ''Savski trg'' (\"Sava Square\").<ref>{{ cite news | author = Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = \u017ditni trg ispred stanice | trans-title = Grains Square in front of the station | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1077 | page = 29 | language = Serbian | date = 20 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1924 the station was connected to [[Po\u017earevac]], and further with eastern Serbia, while in 1928 it was connected to [[Obrenovac]] and [[Sarajevo]]. Soon after, direct connection was established with [[Dubrovnik]] and Zelenika ([[Herceg Novi]]).<ref name=zlatno/><ref name=uskrs/>\n\n=== World War II and reconstruction ===\n\nThe building was damaged during [[World War II]]. It was hit during the [[Operation Retribution (1941)|bombing of Belgrade]], part of the German attack on Yugoslavia on 6 March 1941. Immediately after entering Belgrade, Germans constructed an improvised stationary building  next to the damaged building, on the location where the [[Tito's Blue Train]] was exhibited in 1980. The station was further damaged during the heavy Easter Bombing, conducted by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in 1944. The building was reconstructed after the war, being fully finished in 1953. Two side towers, one of the main architectural and visual marks of the station in the direction of the Kara\u0111or\u0111eva Street, weren't rebuilt but were completely demolished instead.<ref name=tajne/><ref name=uskrs/>\n\nThe post-war reconstruction was headed by the Russian contractors. The clock, placed above the main entrance immediately after the opening in 1885, was also damaged. New mechanism was placed inside and the clock was returned to its original place, but the clock's decorative lace of wrought iron wasn't restored. The door at the main entrance were replaced, but the decoration from the same material as the clock's also hasn't been restored. The glass roof was completely destroyed during the war, but the Russian opted for a built roof instead for restoring the original, glass one. Above the clock, in the [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] there was a coat of arms of the Kingdom of Serbia, held by sculptured, stone winged lions ([[gryphons]]. Above this composition, the Roman numerals MDCCCLXXXIV, marking the year of 1884, were written over the [[architrave]]. New Communist authorities took down the royal coat of arms immediately after taking over after World War II. The stone lions and the [[Cartouche (design)|cartouche]], the decorative round shield around them, were removed later and disappeared after a while. The late 2010s plans for the reconstruction include the restoration of the coat of arms, but none of the other destroyed or removed parts of the building.<ref name=sat>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = Ponovo kuca orijentir za vreme| trans-title = Time teller ticking again | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 27 July 2019 | url = http://www.politika.co.rs/sr/clanak/434567/Beograd/Ponovo-kuca-orijentir-za-vreme}}</ref>\n\nThe coat of arms composition on the tympanum (''fronton'') was {{convert|3.9|m|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|1.15|m|abbr=on}} tall. It was reconstructed in 2019 and made of metal core covered with clay, which is used to make the plaster cast. This cast was used for the new sculpture, which was made of the mix of concrete and three types of crushed [[Ven\u010dac|Aran\u0111elovac stone]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0413\u0440\u0431 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043c \u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0432\u0440\u0430\u045b\u0430 \u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0443 | trans-title = Coat of arms with winged lions returns to Railway station | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 27 October 2019}}</ref> The coat of arms was placed on 11 February 2020.<ref name=grifon/>\n\n=== Post war development ===\n\nIn 1939, 23,298 trains departed from the station. In 1966, there were 60,119 trains with 6.4 million passengers. That same year, half of the international mail from [[Yugoslavia]] was shipped from the station.<ref>{{Citation | title = Rastao je na ru\u0161evinama (reprint on 20 October 2017) | trans-title = (Belgrade) rose on the ruins | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 20 October 1967 }}</ref> The \"golden age\" of the station were the 1970s and 1980s, when the peak of 150 trains per day was reached.<ref name=zlatno/><ref name=\"uskrs\">{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Poslednji Vaskrs Glavne \u017eelezni\u010dke stanice | trans-title = The last Easter of the Main Railway Station | newspaper = Politika | page = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 9 April 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/401633/Poslednji-Vaskrs-Glavne-zeleznicke-stanice }}</ref> Following [[Breakup of Yugoslavia]] in the early 1990s, abrupt demise of railway traffic in Serbia followed, consequences of which are felt also today. Meanwhile, construction of the new [[Belgrade railway junction]] was continued, and plans for dislocating main station to \"Belgrade Center\", colloquially called Prokop, became realistic.\n\nA 1959 plan envisioned urban axis Belgrade Main Railway Station-[[Palace of Serbia|SIV Building]] ([[New Belgrade]]) as the baseline for the future development of both old and new parts of Belgrade. The area between these two points, described as \"two basal foundations\", was to be spanned with nine urban blocks, spreading on both sides of the Sava. Railway station itself was to preserve its function, with additional overhaul which would make it look like the largest railways stations in Europe (\"large lace made of glass and steel\"). Savamala was to be populated with hotels, bus station, terminus for the airport transport, megamarkets, etc. However, disliked by the group of influential architects, in the future development the envisioned urban tissue was effectively \"cut\" in its Savamala section by the new projects, and almost nothing of the planned has done.<ref>{{cite news | author = Radmila Stankovi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0458\u0443 - \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0421\u0442\u0458\u0435\u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b, \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430: \u0414\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0430, \u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0447\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a | trans-title = Interview - Aleksandar Stjepanovi\u0107, architect: There is no dialogue today, today one man rules | newspaper = [[NIN (magazine)|NIN]], No. 3573 | pages = 18\u201321 | language = Serbian | date = 20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the city's general urban plan (GUP) in the 1960s, Cvetni Trg was envisioned as the location of the future central underground [[Belgrade Metro|subway station of Belgrade]], which would also replace the main railway station. The tunnels would conduct the traffic in the north to south direction. The railroad authorities opposed the project, so the plans were abandoned.<ref>{{cite news | author = Arch. \u0110or\u0111e Petrovi\u0107 | title = \u0420\u0443\u0433\u043b\u043e \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e-\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 | trans-title = Eyesore or a modern subway station | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 23 July 1968}}</ref> In 1966, the [[Belgrade Bus Station]] was built, adjoining the station's complex on the north.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a413272/Vesti/Beograd-dobija-privremenu-autobusku-stanicu.html | author = Maja Nikoli\u0107 | title = Posle \u017eelezni\u010dke, u Beogradu i privremena autobuska stanica | trans-title = After the railway, Belgrade is acquiring a bus station, also a temporary one | date = 20 August 2018 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref> Starting with 1967, the Yugoslav Railways pursued an electrification programme, initially focusing on railways in Bosnia and Herzegovina. On 31 May 1970, the Zagreb to Belgrade railway corridor was electrified, and it marked the first time when an electric railway (excluding trams and industrial railways) reached the Serbian soil.\n\nOn 25 September 1968, three steel-made bombs exploded in the station's [[cloakroom]], injuring 13 people. [[Miljenko Hrka\u0107]], member of the [[Terrorism in Yugoslavia#Ustashe terrorism|Ustashe terrorist organization]], planted the bombs, so as earlier that year when on 13 July a bomb exploded in the cinema \"20. Oktobar\", which killed one and injured 86 audience members. Hrka\u0107 was later apprehended, sentenced to death and executed in 1978.<ref>{{cite news | script-title=sr: \u0414\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430 \"20. \u041e\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0440\" \u0443 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 | trans-title = Diversionist from the cinema \"20. Oktobar\" apprehended by our authorities | newspaper = Politika (reprint on 13 June 2019) | language = Serbian | date = 13 June 1969}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Tanjug | script-title=sr: \u041f\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u043f\u0442\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0459\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0425\u0440\u043a\u0430\u045b\u0430 | trans-title = Charges filed against Miljenko Hrka\u0107 | newspaper = Politika (reprint from 22 August 1969) | page = 23 | language = Serbian | date = 22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Closing ===\n\nGradual moving of trains to the new station began in the early 2016. In December 2017, all but two national trains were dislocated to \"Belgrade Center\".<ref name=\"RTS\"/>\n\nProblems arose immediately. The Prokop is still not finished, has no station building and a proper access road and public transportation connections with the rest of the city. Additionally, it has no facilities for loading and unloading cars from the auto trains, nor was ever planned to have one. Still, in January 2018 it was announced that the station will be completely closed for traffic on 1 July 2018, even though none of the projects needed for a complete removal of the railway traffic are finished. The Prokop is incomplete, a projected main goods station in Zemun is not being adapted at all while there is even no project on Belgrade railway beltway.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Posle 134 godine bez vozova u Savskom amfiteatru | trans-title = No more trains in Sava amphitheater after 134 years | newspaper = Politika | pages = 01 & 16 | language = Serbian | date = 16 January 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/396502/Bez-vozova-u-Savskom-amfiteatru-posle-134-godine }}</ref>\n\n=== After shut down ===\n\nAfter closing, the building was removed from the possession of the state railway company and became directly administered by the state.<ref name=sat/>\n\nThe overhaul of the building was planned to start in the autumn of 2018 and to be finished in February 2020. The renovation includes the reconstruction of the fa\u00e7ade and new decorative lights. The venue will then be transformed into the museum. The railway company wanted it to be the museum of the railway, but the government rejected the proposal straightaway, announcing the transformation into the Museum of Medieval Serbia or the Historical Museum.<ref name=obnova/> In February 2020 it was confirmed that the [[Nikola Tesla Museum]] will be relocated here from [[Krunski Venac]], instead of the previously planned location of the Old Power Plant in [[Dor\u0107ol]].<ref name=grifon>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0459\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0431 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u043c \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0443 | trans-title = Royal coat-of-arms on its location again | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 12 February 2020}}</ref> Just few days later, the government stated that they actually didn't decide where the museum will be relocated and that it may be some completely different location.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Dalibotka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Za novu adresu Muzeja Nikole Tesle u igri i tre\u0107a lokacija | trans-title = Third location for the new address of the Nikola Tesla Museum | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 18 February 2020 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/448118/Za-novu-adresu-Muzeja-Nikole-Tesle-u-igri-i-treca-lokacija}}</ref>\n\nProject Belgrade Waterfront envisioned complete change of the square area in front of the building. The plans are to turn it into the plateau with large monument to [[Stefan Nemanja]] in front of the former railway station, facing the Nemanjina Street, named after him. The existing street routes will be turned into the semi-circular crossroad and the traffic will be relocated to the edge of the square. The existing roundabout of the public transportation and a memorial for the 1990-1999 war victims, placed in the 2000s, will be relocated. The existing buildings around the square will be kept, but some will change their purpose.<ref name=resenje>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Tra\u017ei se re\u0161enje za novi Savski trg | trans-title = Quest for the solution for the new Sava Square | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 20 November 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/416202/Trazi-se-resenje-za-novi-Savski-trg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a118765/Vesti/Vucic-za-spomenik-Stefanu-Nemanji.html | author = Tanjug | title = Vu\u010di\u0107 moli Beograd da podigne spomenik Stefanu Nemanji | trans-title = Vu\u010di\u0107 pleads city of Belgrade to build a monument to Stefan Nemanja | date = 15 December 2018 | publisher = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nThe size and the design of the monument to Stefan Nemanja provoked public and artistic criticism. Historian {{ill|Predrag J. Markovi\u0107|sr}} called it the continuation of almost two decades long \"[[Arkan]]ization of the monumental skyline\" in Belgrade,<ref>{{cite news | author = Predrag J. Markovi\u0107 | title = \u0410\u0440\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0435\u0458\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0430 | date = 9 February 2019}}</ref> while [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of the [[University of Arts in Belgrade]], Mileta Prodanovi\u0107, said that the proposed project is devastating for the building of the railway station and that Belgrade is being transformed into [[Skopje 2014|Skopje]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/Kultura/a460013/Prodanovic-o-spomeniku-Bojim-se-da-ce-Beograd-postati-novo-Skoplje.html | author = FoNet| title = Prodanovi\u0107 o spomeniku: Bojim se da \u0107e Beograd postati novo Skoplje | trans-title = Prodanovi\u0107 about the monument: I am afraid that Belgrade will become new Skopje | date = 13 February 2019 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref> President of the Academy of Architecture of Serbia, Bojan Kova\u010devi\u0107 called the project \"irritation\" and a part of the city administration's \"fifth year of spite towards the public and profession\" and \"logorrheic phase of the spatial auto-goals\". He criticized the bidding process as fake and farcical and pointed that important Belgrade architects boycotted the bidding, adding that we \"used to laugh at Skopje\".<ref>{{cite news | author = Bojan Kova\u0107evi\u0107 | title = \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0430\u045a\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0443 | trans-title = Nemanja made to be under the tower | newspaper = Politika-Kulturni dodatak, year LXII, No. 45 | page = 3 | language = Serbian | date = 15\u201316 February 2019}}</ref> Architect Slobodan Maldini pointed to the inadequacies of the competition, including the composition and competency of the jury and a fact that the name of the winner leaked 8 days before it was officially announced. Spanish work is formally flawed as it has no documentation needed, the monument is different in appearance, size and location from the already chosen Russian sculpture. Maldini stated that the competition is a result of the greed and incompetence and described the project as \"unacceptable concreting without ideas\" and the sculpture as pricey and megalomaniacal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://crystalshipghosts.blogspot.com/2019/02/flamenko-i-kazacok-vecernje-novosti-15.html | author = Slobodan Maldini | title = Flamenko i kaza\u010dok | trans-title = Flamenco and kazachok | date = 15 February 2019 | publisher = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nReconstruction of the station's fa\u00e7ade was announced to start in September 2019. The job was given to the \"Koto\" company, which is involved in another controversial project of the city government, [[Kalemegdan Park#Gondola lift|Kalemegdan gondola lift]]. Though the price is much higher than 5 million dinars (\u20ac42,500; estimated to 240 million dinars, or \u20ac2,035,000), which means that the public bidding is obligatory by the law, the government gave the project in direct negotiations with the company, citing \"hastiness due to the weather issues\". Government and city institutions connected with the reconstruction remained silent on any further explanation of the illogicalities regarding the reconstruction: if the building was already left as it is for over a year, why the hastiness all of the sudden; if the weather is a problem, why are the works pushed for the upcoming, winter season; lack of the public invitation to tender; who is really financing the works - the city, the government or the Belgrade Watefront; if this was planned for several years, why are funds secured via the budget reserves and not allocated previously. Deadline is set to February 2020.<ref name=sat/><ref>{{cite news | author = Insajder.net | title = Insajder: Posao restauracije \u017delezni\u010dke stanice dodeljen bez tendera | trans-title = Insajder: Restoration of the Railway Station awarded without tender | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian | date = 4 September 2019 | url = http://rs.n1info.com/Biznis/a522926/Posao-restauracije-Zeleznicke-stanice-dodeljen-bez-tendera.html}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism of shut down ==\n\nThe complete removal of the railway traffic and the total shut down of the station, planned for 1 July 2018,<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Bez vozova u Savskom amfiteatru posle 134 godine | trans-title = No trains anymore in the Sava amphitheater after 134 years | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 15 January 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/396502/Bez-vozova-u-Savskom-amfiteatru-posle-134-godine }}</ref> has been met with the opposition from the experts and public, especially the notion that it has been hastily done because of the highly problematic and controversial Belgrade Waterfront project,<ref name=adio/><ref>{{cite news | author = Karlo Polak | title = Besmisleno je ukinuti \u017eelezni\u010dku stanicu | trans-title = Shutting down the railway station is meaningless | newspaper = Politika | page = 12 | language = Serbian | date = 13 April 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/401859/Pogledi/Besmisleno-je-ukinuti-zeleznicku-stanicu }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bilten.org/?p=22886 | author = Nemanja Pantovi\u0107 | title = Prokop ili kopanje groba za \u017eeleznicu | trans-title = Prokop or digging the grave for the railway | date = 19 March 2018 | publisher = Regionalni portal Bilten.org | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/ekonomija/gasenje-glavne-stanice-stetno-za-putnike-i-grad/ | author = DanasOnline | title = Ga\u0161enje Glavne stanice \u0161tetno za putnike i grad | trans-title = Closing of the Main station is harmful for the passengers and the city | date = 18 January 2018 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/opusteo-simbol-beograda-glavna-zeleznicka-stanica-danas-izgleda-ovako/q3cr18h | author = N.Govoru\u0161a | title = Opusteo simbol Beograda: Glavna \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica danas izgleda ovako | trans-title = Symbol of Belgrade became deserted: this is what the Belgrade Main railway station looks like today | date = 7 January 2018 | publisher = [[Blic]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Ra\u0161trkane stanice i slaba veza sa javnim prevozom | trans-title = Scattered station and weak connection to the public transport | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 19 June 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/405767/Rastrkane-stanice-i-slaba-veza-sa-javnim-prevozom }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Aleksandra Kurte\u0161 | title = \u010cekaju\u0107i voz uz tele\u0107u \u010dorbicu | trans-title = Waiting for the train while eating beef soup | newspaper = Politika | page = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 20 June 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/405840/Cekajuci-voz-uz-telecu-corbicu-FOTO }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/beograd/centar-ostao-bez-vozova-kraj-izgradnje-prokopa-ni-na-vidiku/ | author =  I. Nikoleti\u0107, A. Popovi\u0107 | title = Centar ostao bez vozova, kraj izgradnje \"Prokopa\" ni na vidiku | trans-title = Center without trains, Prokop's construction nowhere near to be finished | date = 19 June 2018 | publisher = Danas | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Aleksandra Pavi\u0107evi\u0107| title = \u041d\u0430\u0436\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0442, (\u043f\u0440\u0435)\u043f\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0458\u0435\u043c\u043e \u0441\u0435 | trans-title = Unfortunately, we know (recognize) us | newspaper = Politika-Kulturni dodatak, Year LXII, No. 13 | pages = 06\u201307 | language = Serbian | date = 7 July 2018}}</ref> while some openly doubt that the investors from the United Arab Emirates really asked for this to happen and that it is all part of a \"special story\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://novaekonomija.rs/tekstovi/poslednji-voz-za-evropu- | author = Aleksandar \u017di\u010d | title = Za\u0161to je zatvorena beogradska \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica - Poslednji voz za Evropu | trans-title = Why is Belgrade railway station closed - Last train to Europe | date = July\u2013August 2018 | publisher = Nova Ekonomija, No. 52 | language = Serbian }}</ref> Especially since, as of June 2018, it was estimated that in the best case scenario Prokop will become fully functional station, with all the necessary and supporting services, only in 2021.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/ekonomija/gradjani-ce-se-zbog-arapa-muciti-da-dodju-do-voza/ | author = G.Vlaovi\u0107 | title = Gra\u0111ani \u0107e se zbog Arapa mu\u010diti da do\u0111u do voza | trans-title = Because of the Arabs, citizens will have hard time reaching the train | date = 21 June 2018 | publisher = Danas | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Belgrade railway station after closing, 2019 05.jpg|thumb|250px|Demolition of the platforms underway by 17 February 2019]]\n\nMember of the [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]] and a public transportation expert, [[Vukan Vu\u010di\u0107]] described the closing of the station and its transfer to Prokop as the \"most disastrous error of the Belgrade transportation\". Citing numerous disadvantages of the new station, he asserted that the old, Main station is way better suited for the railway traffic and that is should be kept. Main station is interconnected by the public transportation lines with almost all parts of Belgrade, and only 6 tram lines go to 11 parts of the city. The location is much better and, as the Belgrade grew around it, practically the entire urban life unfolds around it. He disputed the claim of the city administration that the railway prevents the city to \"come out on the river banks\" as the removal only of the tracks which are not in use will do the trick. The station will be of major importance for the future [[Belgrade Metro]] and, since he said that Prokop, in functional terms, is not a station at all, with closing of the Main station, central Belgrade would not have any proper railway station. Vu\u010di\u0107 concluded that the interests of the investors are superior to those of the commuters. He also maintains that the isolation of the new station's location will directly bring to the further decrease in the number of railway passengers. Another member of the Academy, transportation engineer Du\u0161an Teodorovi\u0107 also criticized the project.<ref name=\"danas\">{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/beograd/prokop-najkatastrofalnija-greska-saobracaja-u-beogradu/ | author = A.Popovi\u0107 | title = Prokop najkatastrofalnija gre\u0161ka saobra\u0107aja u Beogradu | trans-title = Prokop (is) the most disastrous error of the Belgrade transportation | date = 18 April 2018 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Plan za metro u interesu putnika, a ne investitora | trans-title = Plan for the metro (should be) in the interest of the passengers, not of the investors | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 18 April 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/402152/Plan-za-metro-u-interesu-putnika-a-ne-investitora }}</ref>\n\nNenad Kecman, executive manager of the [[Serbian Railways]] stated that none of the objections or suggestions by the experts from the railway transportation branch were adopted by the city administration. New system will marginalize the railway transportation, he added, claiming that the professionals are against both closing of the station, as the entire city gravitates to it, and the planned demolition, or adaptation into the pedestrian bridge, of the [[Old Railway Bridge]]. Saying that such a luxurious complex, like the planned Belgrade Waterfront, can't function without some kind of a railway system, especially for connecting it to the airport, the experts insisted on keeping the old station in at least diminished capacity, but city refused that, claiming that the investors from the United Arab Emirates, which are partners in the Belgrade Waterfront project, rejected any idea of a railway.<ref name=danas/>\n\nArchitect Bojan Kova\u010devi\u0107, president of the Academy of Architecture of Serbia, labeled the hastiness in pushing the Belgrade Waterfront agenda - like the closing of the Main Railway Station even though the new railway facilities weren't finished - as the \"raping\" of Belgrade.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a397085/Biznis/Izmestanje-Glavne-zeleznicke-6-meseci-pre-roka-zasto-se-zuri.html | author = Jelena D. Petrovi\u0107 | title = Izme\u0161tanje Glavne \u017eelezni\u010dke 6 meseci pre roka - \u0161to se \u017euri | trans-title = Relocation of the main railway station 6 months before deadline - what's the hurry? | date = 17 June 2018 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref> Smaller protests against the shut down were organized in the final period, including the day of the closing.<ref name=kaput/>\n\n== Architecture and protection ==\n[[File:Belgrade Railway Station.jpg |thumb|250px |Main entrance at night]]\n\nThe building is constructed after the railway stations of the big European countries and is a monumental edifice.<ref name=\"beogradskonasledje.rs\"/> The project was drafted by the Austrian architect {{ill| Wilhelm von Flattich|de}}, while the definite elaboration of the project was done by Dragi\u0161a Milutinovi\u0107. The contractors were the companies of Neischloss and Freind.<ref name=obnova/>\n\nAt the time of the construction, the building represented one of the most monumental buildings and the symbols of royal capital of that time. It is one of the first railway stations in Serbia, whose design included a specific architectural program and contents adapted to the European technical achievements. It is designed in the style of academism, as a representative edifice, with the dynamic floor plan. The central classicist projection of the main entrance with the triangular tympanum dominates over the architectural composition. With its specific solutions, the building stands as a proof of the technical and architectural development of Serbia in the last decades of the 19th century.\n\nFrom 1980, a [[Tito's Blue Train]] locomotive was put on open display next to the railway station entrance.\n\nThe building was declared a cultural monument in 1981 and the cultural monument of great importance in 1983.<ref name=obnova/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| bgcolor=\"#ECECEC\" | \n<gallery widths=\"150px\" perrow=\"5\" style=\"font-size: small; line-height: 130%;\">\nFile:Belgrade Main railway station 3.jpg|\nFile:Glavna \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica Beograd 1.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade Main railway station 2.jpg|\nFile:\u017dS 441 in Belgrade-Glavna railway station.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade Main railway station (by Pudelek).jpg|\nFile:\u017dS 661 247 at Belgrade Glavna railway station.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade railway station.JPG|\nFile:Belgrade railway station 2.JPG|\nFile:Belgrade Main Railway Station.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade Main Railwaystation at night.JPG|\n</gallery>\n|}\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Belgrade railway junction]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline|Belgrade Main railway station}}\n\n{{Transport in Belgrade}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Belgrade|Main]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1884]]\n[[Category:1884 establishments in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Belgrade Centre railway station}}\n{{Infobox station \n| name          = Belgrade Main Railway Station\n| native_name   = \u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\n| native_name_lang = sr\n| type          = \n| style         = \n| image         = Beograd train station.JPG\n| image_upright = upright\n| image_caption = Station building and surroundings\n| address       = Savski trg 2, [[Belgrade]]\n| map_type            = Serbia Belgrade\n| country       = {{flag|Serbia}}\n| coordinates   = {{coord|44|48|31|N|20|27|20|E|source:kolossus-srwiki|display=inline, title}}\n| line          = \n| connections   = 100 m: [[Belgrade Bus Station]]<br>{{rint|bus|1}} 36, 46, 51, 78, 83, 91, 92, 511, 551, 552, 553, 601, A1, E1<br>{{rint|tram|1}} 2, 3, 7, 9, 12, 13\n| other         = \n| structure     = At-grade\n| platform      = 6 [[bay platform]]s\n| depth         = \n| levels        = \n| tracks        = 13\n| parking       = Yes\n| bicycle       = \n| baggage_check = \n| opened        = {{start date and age|1884|08|23|df=yes}}\n| closed        = {{end date and age|2018|06|30|df=yes}}\n| rebuilt       = \n| electrified   = {{start date and age|1970|05|31|df=yes}}\n| ADA           = \n| code          = \n| owned         = [[Serbian Railways]]\n| zone          = \n| smartcardname = \n| smartcardstatus = \n| former        = \n| passengers    = \n| pass_year     = \n| pass_percent  = \n| pass_system   = \n| mpassengers   = \n| services      = \n| map_locator   = \n}}\n\nThe '''Belgrade Main railway station''' ({{lang-sr|\u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430|\u017delezni\u010dka stanica Beograd Glavna}}) was a [[train station]] in [[Belgrade]], the capital of Serbia. It was built between 1882 and 1885 after the designs of the architect Dragutin Milutinovi\u0107, and it has the status of a [[\u0441ultural monument of great importance]].<ref name=\"beogradskonasledje.rs\">{{cite web|url=http://beogradskonasledje.rs/kd/zavod/savski_venac/zeleznicka_stanica.html |title=\u017delezni\u010dka stanica|publisher=Zavod za za\u0161titu spomenika kulture grada Beograda}}</ref> Until opening of the new [[Belgrade Centre railway station|Belgrade Center station]] (Prokop) in 2016, it was the city's main station, and the busiest train station in the country. In order to free up the space for the [[Belgrade Waterfront]] project, the station was closed on 1 July 2018, and repurposed to become a museum.<ref>[http://balkans.aljazeera.net/vijesti/zgrada-zeljeznicke-stanice-u-beogradu-postaje-muzej Al Jazeera: Zgrada \u017eeljezni\u010dke stanice u Beogradu postaje muzej]</ref>\n\nPassenger trains have been gradually relocated to the new station during 2016 and 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tanjug.rs/full-view_en.aspx?izb=225983 |title=Vucic opens Prokop railway station after 40 years |publisher=Tanjug |date=26 January 2016}}</ref> The most of the national railway traffic was moved to the new station in December 2017, thus leaving only international trains and two trains to Novi Sad in the old station.<ref name=\"RTS\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/drustvo/2966308/prokop-od-danas-glavna-zeleznicka-stanica.html |title=Prokop od danas glavna \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica |date=10 December 2017 |publisher=[[Radio Television of Serbia]]}}</ref> The Main station served its purpose for the last time on 30 June 2018, when the last train, international train 340 to [[Budapest]], left the station at 21:40.<ref name=\"kaput\">{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Oti\u0161ao poslednji voz | trans-title = The last train has left | newspaper = Politika | page = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 1 July 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/406527/Otisao-poslednji-voz-FOTO }}</ref> International trains were relocated to Prokop and train to Bar relocated to the [[Top\u010dider railway station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/404201/Radovi-na-prugama-obimniji-nego-prethodnih-25-godina |title=Radovi na prugama obimniji nego prethodnih 25 godina|first=Goran |last=Volf|publisher=[[Politika]]|date=22 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Origin ===\n\nAt the 1878 [[Congress of Berlin]], Principality of Serbia was [[de jure]] recognized as an independent state and the great powers of the day decided that Serbia should construct the railway. Not economically developed to begin with, Serbia was additionally pauperized after the [[Serbian\u2013Ottoman War (1876\u20131878)|Serbian-Ottoman wars]] from 1876 to 1878, so it lacked the funds. Prince [[Milan Obrenovi\u0107 IV|Milan Obrenovi\u0107]] and the government announced the [[request for tender]] and the bidding was won by a French company. Popular story goes that prince Milan took a bribe of 1 million francs in gold, in order to give the job to the French, but that was never proven.<ref name=\"Politika\">{{Citation | author = Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = Gvozdeni konji u Ciganskoj bari | newspaper = [[Politika]]-Magazin, No. 1039 | pages = 28\u201329 | language = Serbian | date = 27 August 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Construction ===\n\nThe concession included the construction of the [[Belgrade\u2013Ni\u0161 railway]], the train bridge over the [[Sava]] river and a railway which will connect Belgrade to [[Zemun]], at the time, the border town of [[Austria-Hungary]]. The location of the future station building was chosen in 1881.<ref name=tajne>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = Tajne Glavne \u017eelezni\u010dke stanice | trans-title = Secrets of the Main Railway Station | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 16 April 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/427585/Tajne-Glavne-zeleznicke-stanice}}</ref> It was a marshy [[bog]] called ''Ciganska bara'' (\"Gypsy pond\").<ref name=Politika/> The bog was charted for the first time in an [[Austria]]n map from 1789. It was a marsh which covered a wide area from the modern ''Kara\u0111or\u0111eva'' street to the mouth of the [[Top\u010diderska Reka]] into the Sava, across the northern tip of [[Ada Ciganlija]]. The marshy area covered the today's location of the Belgrade Main railway station and parts of the ''Sarajevska'' and ''Hajduk-Veljkov venac'' streets. Ciganska bara drained two other bogs. One  was located on [[Slavija Square|Slavija]], which drained through the creek of ''Vra\u010darski potok''<ref>{{Citation | author = Dragana Joki\u0107 Stamenkovi\u0107| title = Beograd na dvesta sputanih voda| newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 28 May 2011 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/178840/Beograd-na-dvesta-sputanih-voda }}</ref> which flew down the area of the today's [[Nemanjina Street]]. The other pond was [[Zeleni Venac]]. [[Gypsies]] who lived in the area, hence the name, used the mud from the bog to make roof tiles. They lived in small huts or caravans (called \"\u010derge\"), between the high grass and [[Juncaceae|rush]], with their horses and water buffaloes grazing freely in the area. As most of the huts were actually [[stilt house]]s, built on [[deep foundation|piles]] due to the marshy land, the area was gradually named [[Bara Venecija]] (\"[[Venice]] pond\").<ref name=ack>{{Citation | author = Dragoljub Ackovi\u0107| title = \u0160est vekova Roma u Beogradu \u2013 part XV, Veselje do kasno u no\u0107 | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nAs such, the location was absolutely inappropriate for any construction work and the marsh had to be filled first. The remains of the demolished [[Republic Square (Belgrade)#Stambol Gate|Stambol Gate]] in 1866 also finished in the bog.<ref name=tajne/> By 1884 the bog was drained and buried under the rubble from all parts of the city but especially from [[Prokop (Belgrade)|Prokop]],<ref name=ack/> Prokop is located in the eastern section of the former neighborhood of [[Jatagan Mala]]. Previously, it was a geographical reference, as the area was located in the lower valley of the now underground stream of [[Mokrolu\u0161ki Potok]]. Earth and gravel were dug and used to cover and drain the swamps on the Sava's right bank, so that neighborhoods of [[Savamala]] and [[Bara Venecija]] could be constructed, along with the building of central railway station. After the works were completed, the area around Mokrolu\u0161ki Potok was left as a steep, elongated cut in the ground and so got its name (Serbian ''prokop'', cut or dug through). Prince Milan personally suggested this area, which stretched above the [[\u0110or\u0111e Vajfert]]'s brewery and the neighborhood of [[Mostar interchange#Neighborhood|Smutekovac]]. He cited many reasons like the quality of the earth or closeness to the construction site which would reduce the transportation costs. However, that land belonged to his wife, [[Natalie of Serbia|Princess Natalie]], so the prince even earned money from the station's construction. In a historical twist, the Prokop is today location of the future central railway station in Belgrade.<ref name=Politika/>\n\nWhen the location was chosen, it was also disconnected from Belgrade in terms of transportation. Former village of Savamala was the closest, but the city could be reached only by the [[fiaker]]s, using a bypass route via the Spomeni\u010dka Street (modern Nemanjina).<ref name=tajne/>\n\nBuilding of the railway and the station initially met with fierce opposition. The law on railway construction barely passed in the National Assembly of Serbia, while for the railway itself it was said that it is too costly but unnecessary, a devil's snake, destroyer of the people, where it passes women bare less children and a way for foreign powers to infiltrate the state.<ref>{{cite news | author = Darko Pejovi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0418\u0437 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0435\u043c\u043d\u0435 \u043a\u0443\u045b\u0435 \u0443 \u043f\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043d\u0443 \u0432\u0438\u043b\u0443 | trans-title = From ground floor house to five-floor villa | newspaper = Politika | page = 11 | language = Serbian | date = 28 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{Belgrade Main railway station}}\n\n=== Opening ===\n\nThe [[foundation stone]]s were laid by prince Milan: for the railway on {{OldStyleDate|3 July|1881|21 June}}, for the station on {{OldStyleDate|15 April|1883|3 April}}. The building of the station lagged behind the construction of the railway and the bridge, so when the time came for the first train to pass through Belgrade, the object wasn't finished. As it was obvious that the station won't be finished on time, the temporary object was built to serve the purpose instead. Even though at one point in 1884 it was recorded that 5,575 workers were employed on the building's construction, it couldn't be finished in time.<ref name=obnova>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u041e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0435 \u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0435 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0435 | trans-title = Reconstruction of the former building of the Main railway station | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 6 August 2019 }}</ref> It had to be ceremonially open, even though it was still covered with scaffolds.<ref name=Politika/> The first train from this station departed towards [[Zemun]] with courtly honours, on {{OldStyleDate|1 September|1884|20 August}}, at 3 p.m.<ref>Srpske novine, 21 August 1884</ref> As Serbia was declared a kingdom in 1882, the first passengers were now King Milan, Queen Natalie and the Crown Prince [[Aleksandar Obrenovi\u0107|Alexander]], on the way to [[Vienna]]. More than 200 foreign guests and couple of thousands of citizens attended the opening ceremony.<ref>[http://arhiva.24sata.rs/vesti/beograd/vest/na-mestu-zeleznicke-stanice-pre-dva-veka-bila-je-bara/31459.phtml \u201eNa mestu \u017eelezni\u010dke stanice pre dva veka bila je bara\u201c, 24 Sata], 5 March 2012.</ref>\n\nMilitary orchestra played music all the way until the train crossed the bridge. Three days later the station was again decorated with flags and flowers as the railway to Ni\u0161 was open and the first, promotional composition towards Ni\u0161 departed. Cannons from the [[Belgrade Fortress]] marked the occasion while the military orchestras played marches. The journal ''Novi beogradski dnevnik'' wrote: \"Young and old, rich and poor, pretty and ugly, they all gathered in Bara Venecija to see the start of the first Serbian railway\". The first train departed at 8:45, with 100 passengers in nine cars with three classes. Just to accommodate the huge crowds of journalists and cheering citizens, another train departed just five minutes later.<ref name=Politika/>\n\nThe first passenger line started on {{OldStyleDate|16 September|1884|4 September}} at 8:30. It was a line to Ni\u0161, and the train had 20 cars with 200 passengers.<ref name=adio>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Od sve\u010darskih topova do \"A sad, adio\" | trans-title = From ceremonial cannons to \"And now, adio\" | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 5 September 2019 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/437263/Od-svecarskih-topova-do-A-sad-adio}}</ref> On the same day, the line to [[Budapest|Pest]] was established, and at the beginning only two trains a day departed on these lines.<ref>Srpske novine, 2 September 1884</ref> Archbishop of Belgrade and Metropolitan of Serbia, Teodosije Mraovi\u0107, blessed the two first locomotives. The regular traffic was established 10 days later.<ref name=adio/> Until the station was finished, a small building in front of it functioned as a temporary facility (ticket booths, administration, etc.). On that spot, today is exhibited a steam locomotive, just in front of the building.<ref name=\"Politika\"/> The fully finished station became operational on 21 September 1885.<ref name=obnova/>\n\nAt the time, the central section of the building was occupied by the offices of the station's personnel, [[telephone exchange]], [[telegraph]], cashier boxes, wardrobes and police offices. The left wing of the station was adapted into the royal waiting room, while the right one was for the regular passenger. In this section there were also restaurants, while the upper floor was occupied by the living quarters for the station's employees.<ref name=adio/>\n\n=== Later developments ===\n\nAfter being completed in September 1885 and soon became the most important railway hub in this part of Europe. In 1888 it became a stop on the [[Orient Express]] route and in 1892 a ceremonial reception for [[Nikola Tesla]] was organized. The very first car in Belgrade arrived by train, via the main station, on 3 April 1903.<ref>{{cite news | author = Goran Vesi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u045b\u0430\u0458\u043d\u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a \u0443 \u043b\u0438\u043a\u0443 \u041c\u0438\u043a\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u0443\u0441\u0430 | trans-title = First traffic sign was shaped like Mickey Mouse | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 5 April 2019}}</ref><ref name=zlatno>{{Citation |author= Dejan Aleksi\u0107 |title= A vozovi prolaze - 133 godine |newspaper= Politika |page= 16 |language= Serbian |date= 4 September 2017 }}</ref> The building originally had a gas lighting, which was later replaced with the electrical one. As it was a major consumer, it was decided that the building will have its own power generator.  A mini electrical plant was built next to the station building  in 1909 and demolished in 1929, when the building of the Post Office No. 6 was built instead.<ref name=tajne/>\n\nAfter the station was finished, the area to the east developed into the square which, due to its location close both to the railway and the port, served for the transshipment of the goods, especially the cereals and grains, so in time it was named ''\u017ditni trg'' (\"Grains square\"). It was also well connected with the roads which lead outside of the city. It was directly connected with the road which is today the ''Savska'' Street in the direction of the [[Mostar interchange|Mostar]] neighborhood. There, it was splitting in two directions, one to the east (later neighborhoods of [[Jatagan Mala]] and [[Prokop (Belgrade)|Prokop]]) in the direction of [[Kragujevac]] in central Serbia, and the other to the south (neighborhoods of [[Senjak]], [[\u010cukarica]], [[\u017darkovo]]) and further to the west Serbia. The square was renamed ''Vilsonov trg'' (\"Wilson's Square\") after World War I, in honor of the US president [[Woodrow Wilson]] and today in named ''Savski trg'' (\"Sava Square\").<ref>{{ cite news | author = Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = \u017ditni trg ispred stanice | trans-title = Grains Square in front of the station | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1077 | page = 29 | language = Serbian | date = 20 May 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1924 the station was connected to [[Po\u017earevac]], and further with eastern Serbia, while in 1928 it was connected to [[Obrenovac]] and [[Sarajevo]]. Soon after, direct connection was established with [[Dubrovnik]] and Zelenika ([[Herceg Novi]]).<ref name=zlatno/><ref name=uskrs/>\n\n=== World War II and reconstruction ===\n\nThe building was damaged during [[World War II]]. It was hit during the [[Operation Retribution (1941)|bombing of Belgrade]], part of the German attack on Yugoslavia on 6 March 1941. Immediately after entering Belgrade, Germans constructed an improvised stationary building  next to the damaged building, on the location where the [[Tito's Blue Train]] was exhibited in 1980. The station was further damaged during the heavy Easter Bombing, conducted by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] in 1944. The building was reconstructed after the war, being fully finished in 1953. Two side towers, one of the main architectural and visual marks of the station in the direction of the Kara\u0111or\u0111eva Street, weren't rebuilt but were completely demolished instead.<ref name=tajne/><ref name=uskrs/>\n\nThe post-war reconstruction was headed by the Russian contractors. The clock, placed above the main entrance immediately after the opening in 1885, was also damaged. New mechanism was placed inside and the clock was returned to its original place, but the clock's decorative lace of wrought iron wasn't restored. The door at the main entrance were replaced, but the decoration from the same material as the clock's also hasn't been restored. The glass roof was completely destroyed during the war, but the Russian opted for a built roof instead for restoring the original, glass one. Above the clock, in the [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] there was a coat of arms of the Kingdom of Serbia, held by sculptured, stone winged lions ([[gryphons]]. Above this composition, the Roman numerals MDCCCLXXXIV, marking the year of 1884, were written over the [[architrave]]. New Communist authorities took down the royal coat of arms immediately after taking over after World War II. The stone lions and the [[Cartouche (design)|cartouche]], the decorative round shield around them, were removed later and disappeared after a while. The late 2010s plans for the reconstruction include the restoration of the coat of arms, but none of the other destroyed or removed parts of the building.<ref name=sat>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = Ponovo kuca orijentir za vreme| trans-title = Time teller ticking again | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 27 July 2019 | url = http://www.politika.co.rs/sr/clanak/434567/Beograd/Ponovo-kuca-orijentir-za-vreme}}</ref>\n\nThe coat of arms composition on the tympanum (''fronton'') was {{convert|3.9|m|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|1.15|m|abbr=on}} tall. It was reconstructed in 2019 and made of metal core covered with clay, which is used to make the plaster cast. This cast was used for the new sculpture, which was made of the mix of concrete and three types of crushed [[Ven\u010dac|Aran\u0111elovac stone]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0413\u0440\u0431 \u0441 \u043a\u0440\u0438\u043b\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043c \u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c\u0430 \u0432\u0440\u0430\u045b\u0430 \u0441\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0416\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0443 | trans-title = Coat of arms with winged lions returns to Railway station | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 27 October 2019}}</ref> The coat of arms was placed on 11 February 2020.<ref name=grifon/>\n\n=== Post war development ===\n\nIn 1939, 23,298 trains departed from the station. In 1966, there were 60,119 trains with 6.4 million passengers. That same year, half of the international mail from [[Yugoslavia]] was shipped from the station.<ref>{{Citation | title = Rastao je na ru\u0161evinama (reprint on 20 October 2017) | trans-title = (Belgrade) rose on the ruins | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 20 October 1967 }}</ref> The \"golden age\" of the station were the 1970s and 1980s, when the peak of 150 trains per day was reached.<ref name=zlatno/><ref name=\"uskrs\">{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Poslednji Vaskrs Glavne \u017eelezni\u010dke stanice | trans-title = The last Easter of the Main Railway Station | newspaper = Politika | page = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 9 April 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/401633/Poslednji-Vaskrs-Glavne-zeleznicke-stanice }}</ref> Following [[Breakup of Yugoslavia]] in the early 1990s, abrupt demise of railway traffic in Serbia followed, consequences of which are felt also today. Meanwhile, construction of the new [[Belgrade railway junction]] was continued, and plans for dislocating main station to \"Belgrade Center\", colloquially called Prokop, became realistic.\n\nA 1959 plan envisioned urban axis Belgrade Main Railway Station-[[Palace of Serbia|SIV Building]] ([[New Belgrade]]) as the baseline for the future development of both old and new parts of Belgrade. The area between these two points, described as \"two basal foundations\", was to be spanned with nine urban blocks, spreading on both sides of the Sava. Railway station itself was to preserve its function, with additional overhaul which would make it look like the largest railways stations in Europe (\"large lace made of glass and steel\"). Savamala was to be populated with hotels, bus station, terminus for the airport transport, megamarkets, etc. However, disliked by the group of influential architects, in the future development the envisioned urban tissue was effectively \"cut\" in its Savamala section by the new projects, and almost nothing of the planned has done.<ref>{{cite news | author = Radmila Stankovi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u0458\u0443 - \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440 \u0421\u0442\u0458\u0435\u043f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u045b, \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430: \u0414\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u0434\u0438\u0458\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0430, \u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0458\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0447\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a | trans-title = Interview - Aleksandar Stjepanovi\u0107, architect: There is no dialogue today, today one man rules | newspaper = [[NIN (magazine)|NIN]], No. 3573 | pages = 18\u201321 | language = Serbian | date = 20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the city's general urban plan (GUP) in the 1960s, Cvetni Trg was envisioned as the location of the future central underground [[Belgrade Metro|subway station of Belgrade]], which would also replace the main railway station. The tunnels would conduct the traffic in the north to south direction. The railroad authorities opposed the project, so the plans were abandoned.<ref>{{cite news | author = Arch. \u0110or\u0111e Petrovi\u0107 | title = \u0420\u0443\u0433\u043b\u043e \u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e-\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 | trans-title = Eyesore or a modern subway station | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 23 July 1968}}</ref> In 1966, the [[Belgrade Bus Station]] was built, adjoining the station's complex on the north.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a413272/Vesti/Beograd-dobija-privremenu-autobusku-stanicu.html | author = Maja Nikoli\u0107 | title = Posle \u017eelezni\u010dke, u Beogradu i privremena autobuska stanica | trans-title = After the railway, Belgrade is acquiring a bus station, also a temporary one | date = 20 August 2018 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref> Starting with 1967, the Yugoslav Railways pursued an electrification programme, initially focusing on railways in Bosnia and Herzegovina. On 31 May 1970, the Zagreb to Belgrade railway corridor was electrified, and it marked the first time when an electric railway (excluding trams and industrial railways) reached the Serbian soil.\n\nOn 25 September 1968, three steel-made bombs exploded in the station's [[cloakroom]], injuring 13 people. [[Miljenko Hrka\u0107]], member of the [[Terrorism in Yugoslavia#Ustashe terrorism|Ustashe terrorist organization]], planted the bombs, so as earlier that year when on 13 July a bomb exploded in the cinema \"20. Oktobar\", which killed one and injured 86 audience members. Hrka\u0107 was later apprehended, sentenced to death and executed in 1978.<ref>{{cite news | script-title=sr: \u0414\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0438\u0437 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0430 \"20. \u041e\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0430\u0440\" \u0443 \u0440\u0443\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0430 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 | trans-title = Diversionist from the cinema \"20. Oktobar\" apprehended by our authorities | newspaper = Politika (reprint on 13 June 2019) | language = Serbian | date = 13 June 1969}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Tanjug | script-title=sr: \u041f\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0433\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0430 \u043e\u043f\u0442\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u041c\u0438\u0459\u0435\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0425\u0440\u043a\u0430\u045b\u0430 | trans-title = Charges filed against Miljenko Hrka\u0107 | newspaper = Politika (reprint from 22 August 1969) | page = 23 | language = Serbian | date = 22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Closing ===\n\nGradual moving of trains to the new station began in the early 2016. In December 2017, all but two national trains were dislocated to \"Belgrade Center\".<ref name=\"RTS\"/>\n\nProblems arose immediately. The Prokop is still not finished, has no station building and a proper access road and public transportation connections with the rest of the city. Additionally, it has no facilities for loading and unloading cars from the auto trains, nor was ever planned to have one. Still, in January 2018 it was announced that the station will be completely closed for traffic on 1 July 2018, even though none of the projects needed for a complete removal of the railway traffic are finished. The Prokop is incomplete, a projected main goods station in Zemun is not being adapted at all while there is even no project on Belgrade railway beltway.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Posle 134 godine bez vozova u Savskom amfiteatru | trans-title = No more trains in Sava amphitheater after 134 years | newspaper = Politika | pages = 01 & 16 | language = Serbian | date = 16 January 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/396502/Bez-vozova-u-Savskom-amfiteatru-posle-134-godine }}</ref>\n\n=== After shut down ===\n\nAfter closing, the building was removed from the possession of the state railway company and became directly administered by the state.<ref name=sat/>\n\nThe overhaul of the building was planned to start in the autumn of 2018 and to be finished in February 2020. The renovation includes the reconstruction of the fa\u00e7ade and new decorative lights. The venue will then be transformed into the museum. The railway company wanted it to be the museum of the railway, but the government rejected the proposal straightaway, announcing the transformation into the Museum of Medieval Serbia or the Historical Museum.<ref name=obnova/> In February 2020 it was confirmed that the [[Nikola Tesla Museum]] will be relocated here from [[Krunski Venac]], instead of the previously planned location of the Old Power Plant in [[Dor\u0107ol]].<ref name=grifon>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0459\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0431 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u043c \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0443 | trans-title = Royal coat-of-arms on its location again | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 12 February 2020}}</ref> Just few days later, the government stated that they actually didn't decide where the museum will be relocated and that it may be some completely different location.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Dalibotka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Za novu adresu Muzeja Nikole Tesle u igri i tre\u0107a lokacija | trans-title = Third location for the new address of the Nikola Tesla Museum | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 18 February 2020 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/448118/Za-novu-adresu-Muzeja-Nikole-Tesle-u-igri-i-treca-lokacija}}</ref>\n\nProject Belgrade Waterfront envisioned complete change of the square area in front of the building. The plans are to turn it into the plateau with large monument to [[Stefan Nemanja]] in front of the former railway station, facing the Nemanjina Street, named after him. The existing street routes will be turned into the semi-circular crossroad and the traffic will be relocated to the edge of the square. The existing roundabout of the public transportation and a memorial for the 1990-1999 war victims, placed in the 2000s, will be relocated. The existing buildings around the square will be kept, but some will change their purpose.<ref name=resenje>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Tra\u017ei se re\u0161enje za novi Savski trg | trans-title = Quest for the solution for the new Sava Square | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 20 November 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/416202/Trazi-se-resenje-za-novi-Savski-trg}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a118765/Vesti/Vucic-za-spomenik-Stefanu-Nemanji.html | author = Tanjug | title = Vu\u010di\u0107 moli Beograd da podigne spomenik Stefanu Nemanji | trans-title = Vu\u010di\u0107 pleads city of Belgrade to build a monument to Stefan Nemanja | date = 15 December 2018 | publisher = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nThe size and the design of the monument to Stefan Nemanja provoked public and artistic criticism. Historian {{ill|Predrag J. Markovi\u0107|sr}} called it the continuation of almost two decades long \"[[Arkan]]ization of the monumental skyline\" in Belgrade,<ref>{{cite news | author = Predrag J. Markovi\u0107 | title = \u0410\u0440\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0458\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0435\u0458\u0441\u0430\u0436\u0430 | date = 9 February 2019}}</ref> while [[Rector (academia)|rector]] of the [[University of Arts in Belgrade]], Mileta Prodanovi\u0107, said that the proposed project is devastating for the building of the railway station and that Belgrade is being transformed into [[Skopje 2014|Skopje]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/Kultura/a460013/Prodanovic-o-spomeniku-Bojim-se-da-ce-Beograd-postati-novo-Skoplje.html | author = FoNet| title = Prodanovi\u0107 o spomeniku: Bojim se da \u0107e Beograd postati novo Skoplje | trans-title = Prodanovi\u0107 about the monument: I am afraid that Belgrade will become new Skopje | date = 13 February 2019 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref> President of the Academy of Architecture of Serbia, Bojan Kova\u010devi\u0107 called the project \"irritation\" and a part of the city administration's \"fifth year of spite towards the public and profession\" and \"logorrheic phase of the spatial auto-goals\". He criticized the bidding process as fake and farcical and pointed that important Belgrade architects boycotted the bidding, adding that we \"used to laugh at Skopje\".<ref>{{cite news | author = Bojan Kova\u0107evi\u0107 | title = \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0430\u045a\u0430 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u0443 | trans-title = Nemanja made to be under the tower | newspaper = Politika-Kulturni dodatak, year LXII, No. 45 | page = 3 | language = Serbian | date = 15\u201316 February 2019}}</ref> Architect Slobodan Maldini pointed to the inadequacies of the competition, including the composition and competency of the jury and a fact that the name of the winner leaked 8 days before it was officially announced. Spanish work is formally flawed as it has no documentation needed, the monument is different in appearance, size and location from the already chosen Russian sculpture. Maldini stated that the competition is a result of the greed and incompetence and described the project as \"unacceptable concreting without ideas\" and the sculpture as pricey and megalomaniacal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://crystalshipghosts.blogspot.com/2019/02/flamenko-i-kazacok-vecernje-novosti-15.html | author = Slobodan Maldini | title = Flamenko i kaza\u010dok | trans-title = Flamenco and kazachok | date = 15 February 2019 | publisher = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nReconstruction of the station's fa\u00e7ade was announced to start in September 2019. The job was given to the \"Koto\" company, which is involved in another controversial project of the city government, [[Kalemegdan Park#Gondola lift|Kalemegdan gondola lift]]. Though the price is much higher than 5 million dinars (\u20ac42,500; estimated to 240 million dinars, or \u20ac2,035,000), which means that the public bidding is obligatory by the law, the government gave the project in direct negotiations with the company, citing \"hastiness due to the weather issues\". Government and city institutions connected with the reconstruction remained silent on any further explanation of the illogicalities regarding the reconstruction: if the building was already left as it is for over a year, why the hastiness all of the sudden; if the weather is a problem, why are the works pushed for the upcoming, winter season; lack of the public invitation to tender; who is really financing the works - the city, the government or the Belgrade Watefront; if this was planned for several years, why are funds secured via the budget reserves and not allocated previously. Deadline is set to February 2020.<ref name=sat/><ref>{{cite news | author = Insajder.net | title = Insajder: Posao restauracije \u017delezni\u010dke stanice dodeljen bez tendera | trans-title = Insajder: Restoration of the Railway Station awarded without tender | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian | date = 4 September 2019 | url = http://rs.n1info.com/Biznis/a522926/Posao-restauracije-Zeleznicke-stanice-dodeljen-bez-tendera.html}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism of shut down ==\n\nThe complete removal of the railway traffic and the total shut down of the station, planned for 1 July 2018,<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Bez vozova u Savskom amfiteatru posle 134 godine | trans-title = No trains anymore in the Sava amphitheater after 134 years | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 15 January 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/396502/Bez-vozova-u-Savskom-amfiteatru-posle-134-godine }}</ref> has been met with the opposition from the experts and public, especially the notion that it has been hastily done because of the highly problematic and controversial Belgrade Waterfront project,<ref name=adio/><ref>{{cite news | author = Karlo Polak | title = Besmisleno je ukinuti \u017eelezni\u010dku stanicu | trans-title = Shutting down the railway station is meaningless | newspaper = Politika | page = 12 | language = Serbian | date = 13 April 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/401859/Pogledi/Besmisleno-je-ukinuti-zeleznicku-stanicu }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bilten.org/?p=22886 | author = Nemanja Pantovi\u0107 | title = Prokop ili kopanje groba za \u017eeleznicu | trans-title = Prokop or digging the grave for the railway | date = 19 March 2018 | publisher = Regionalni portal Bilten.org | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/ekonomija/gasenje-glavne-stanice-stetno-za-putnike-i-grad/ | author = DanasOnline | title = Ga\u0161enje Glavne stanice \u0161tetno za putnike i grad | trans-title = Closing of the Main station is harmful for the passengers and the city | date = 18 January 2018 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/opusteo-simbol-beograda-glavna-zeleznicka-stanica-danas-izgleda-ovako/q3cr18h | author = N.Govoru\u0161a | title = Opusteo simbol Beograda: Glavna \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica danas izgleda ovako | trans-title = Symbol of Belgrade became deserted: this is what the Belgrade Main railway station looks like today | date = 7 January 2018 | publisher = [[Blic]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Ra\u0161trkane stanice i slaba veza sa javnim prevozom | trans-title = Scattered station and weak connection to the public transport | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 19 June 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/405767/Rastrkane-stanice-i-slaba-veza-sa-javnim-prevozom }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Aleksandra Kurte\u0161 | title = \u010cekaju\u0107i voz uz tele\u0107u \u010dorbicu | trans-title = Waiting for the train while eating beef soup | newspaper = Politika | page = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 20 June 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/405840/Cekajuci-voz-uz-telecu-corbicu-FOTO }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/beograd/centar-ostao-bez-vozova-kraj-izgradnje-prokopa-ni-na-vidiku/ | author =  I. Nikoleti\u0107, A. Popovi\u0107 | title = Centar ostao bez vozova, kraj izgradnje \"Prokopa\" ni na vidiku | trans-title = Center without trains, Prokop's construction nowhere near to be finished | date = 19 June 2018 | publisher = Danas | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Aleksandra Pavi\u0107evi\u0107| title = \u041d\u0430\u0436\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0442, (\u043f\u0440\u0435)\u043f\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0458\u0435\u043c\u043e \u0441\u0435 | trans-title = Unfortunately, we know (recognize) us | newspaper = Politika-Kulturni dodatak, Year LXII, No. 13 | pages = 06\u201307 | language = Serbian | date = 7 July 2018}}</ref> while some openly doubt that the investors from the United Arab Emirates really asked for this to happen and that it is all part of a \"special story\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://novaekonomija.rs/tekstovi/poslednji-voz-za-evropu- | author = Aleksandar \u017di\u010d | title = Za\u0161to je zatvorena beogradska \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica - Poslednji voz za Evropu | trans-title = Why is Belgrade railway station closed - Last train to Europe | date = July\u2013August 2018 | publisher = Nova Ekonomija, No. 52 | language = Serbian }}</ref> Especially since, as of June 2018, it was estimated that in the best case scenario Prokop will become fully functional station, with all the necessary and supporting services, only in 2021.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/ekonomija/gradjani-ce-se-zbog-arapa-muciti-da-dodju-do-voza/ | author = G.Vlaovi\u0107 | title = Gra\u0111ani \u0107e se zbog Arapa mu\u010diti da do\u0111u do voza | trans-title = Because of the Arabs, citizens will have hard time reaching the train | date = 21 June 2018 | publisher = Danas | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Belgrade railway station after closing, 2019 05.jpg|thumb|250px|Demolition of the platforms underway by 17 February 2019]]\n\nMember of the [[Serbian Academy of Sciences and Arts]] and a public transportation expert, [[Vukan Vu\u010di\u0107]] described the closing of the station and its transfer to Prokop as the \"most disastrous error of the Belgrade transportation\". Citing numerous disadvantages of the new station, he asserted that the old, Main station is way better suited for the railway traffic and that is should be kept. Main station is interconnected by the public transportation lines with almost all parts of Belgrade, and only 6 tram lines go to 11 parts of the city. The location is much better and, as the Belgrade grew around it, practically the entire urban life unfolds around it. He disputed the claim of the city administration that the railway prevents the city to \"come out on the river banks\" as the removal only of the tracks which are not in use will do the trick. The station will be of major importance for the future [[Belgrade Metro]] and, since he said that Prokop, in functional terms, is not a station at all, with closing of the Main station, central Belgrade would not have any proper railway station. Vu\u010di\u0107 concluded that the interests of the investors are superior to those of the commuters. He also maintains that the isolation of the new station's location will directly bring to the further decrease in the number of railway passengers. Another member of the Academy, transportation engineer Du\u0161an Teodorovi\u0107 also criticized the project.<ref name=\"danas\">{{cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/beograd/prokop-najkatastrofalnija-greska-saobracaja-u-beogradu/ | author = A.Popovi\u0107 | title = Prokop najkatastrofalnija gre\u0161ka saobra\u0107aja u Beogradu | trans-title = Prokop (is) the most disastrous error of the Belgrade transportation | date = 18 April 2018 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Plan za metro u interesu putnika, a ne investitora | trans-title = Plan for the metro (should be) in the interest of the passengers, not of the investors | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 18 April 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/402152/Plan-za-metro-u-interesu-putnika-a-ne-investitora }}</ref>\n\nNenad Kecman, executive manager of the [[Serbian Railways]] stated that none of the objections or suggestions by the experts from the railway transportation branch were adopted by the city administration. New system will marginalize the railway transportation, he added, claiming that the professionals are against both closing of the station, as the entire city gravitates to it, and the planned demolition, or adaptation into the pedestrian bridge, of the [[Old Railway Bridge]]. Saying that such a luxurious complex, like the planned Belgrade Waterfront, can't function without some kind of a railway system, especially for connecting it to the airport, the experts insisted on keeping the old station in at least diminished capacity, but city refused that, claiming that the investors from the United Arab Emirates, which are partners in the Belgrade Waterfront project, rejected any idea of a railway.<ref name=danas/>\n\nArchitect Bojan Kova\u010devi\u0107, president of the Academy of Architecture of Serbia, labeled the hastiness in pushing the Belgrade Waterfront agenda - like the closing of the Main Railway Station even though the new railway facilities weren't finished - as the \"raping\" of Belgrade.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a397085/Biznis/Izmestanje-Glavne-zeleznicke-6-meseci-pre-roka-zasto-se-zuri.html | author = Jelena D. Petrovi\u0107 | title = Izme\u0161tanje Glavne \u017eelezni\u010dke 6 meseci pre roka - \u0161to se \u017euri | trans-title = Relocation of the main railway station 6 months before deadline - what's the hurry? | date = 17 June 2018 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref> Smaller protests against the shut down were organized in the final period, including the day of the closing.<ref name=kaput/>\n\n== Architecture and protection ==\n[[File:Belgrade Railway Station.jpg |thumb|250px |Main entrance at night]]\n\nThe building is constructed after the railway stations of the big European countries and is a monumental edifice.<ref name=\"beogradskonasledje.rs\"/> The project was drafted by the Austrian architect {{ill| Wilhelm von Flattich|de}}, while the definite elaboration of the project was done by Dragi\u0161a Milutinovi\u0107. The contractors were the companies of Neischloss and Freind.<ref name=obnova/>\n\nAt the time of the construction, the building represented one of the most monumental buildings and the symbols of royal capital of that time. It is one of the first railway stations in Serbia, whose design included a specific architectural program and contents adapted to the European technical achievements. It is designed in the style of academism, as a representative edifice, with the dynamic floor plan. The central classicist projection of the main entrance with the triangular tympanum dominates over the architectural composition. With its specific solutions, the building stands as a proof of the technical and architectural development of Serbia in the last decades of the 19th century.\n\nFrom 1980, a [[Tito's Blue Train]] locomotive was put on open display next to the railway station entrance.\n\nThe building was declared a cultural monument in 1981 and the cultural monument of great importance in 1983.<ref name=obnova/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n| bgcolor=\"#ECECEC\" | \n<gallery widths=\"150px\" perrow=\"5\" style=\"font-size: small; line-height: 130%;\">\nFile:Belgrade Main railway station 3.jpg|\nFile:Glavna \u017eelezni\u010dka stanica Beograd 1.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade Main railway station 2.jpg|\nFile:\u017dS 441 in Belgrade-Glavna railway station.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade Main railway station (by Pudelek).jpg|\nFile:\u017dS 661 247 at Belgrade Glavna railway station.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade railway station.JPG|\nFile:Belgrade railway station 2.JPG|\nFile:Belgrade Main Railway Station.jpg|\nFile:Belgrade Main Railwaystation at night.JPG|\n</gallery>\n|}\n</center>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Belgrade railway junction]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category-inline|Belgrade Main railway station}}\n\n{{Transport in Belgrade}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Belgrade|Main]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1884]]\n[[Category:1884 establishments in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 2018]]\n", "name_user": "Marko1973", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stylistic edits.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belgrade_Main_railway_station"}
